{"title_page": "Festival di Napoli", "text_new": "{{Infobox music festival\n| name         = Festival della Canzone Napoletana<br>(Festival of Neapolitan Song)\n| image        = File:Ornella Vanoni al Festival di Napoli 1964.jpg\n| caption      = [[Ornella Vanoni]] at the festival in 1964\n| location     = [[Italy]]\n| years_active = 1952\u20131971<br>1981<br>1998\u20132004\n| founders     = [[RAI]]\n| dates        =\n| genre        = [[Neapolitan song]], [[folk music]], [[classical music]], [[pop music]], [[rock music]], etc.\n| attendance   = \n| capacity     =\n| website      =\n}}\nThe '''Festival della Canzone Napoletana''' (\"Festival of Neapolitan Song\"), commonly known as the '''Festival di Napoli''', is a [[Neapolitan song]] contest. The first edition was held in 1952 and the last in 2004. From 1952 to 1970 the show was broadcast on [[RAI]] and from 1998 to 2004, in a differently spirited version, by [[Rete 4]].\n\n== History ==\nA symbol of [[Neapolitan song]] of the second half of the twentieth century, the Festival della Canzone Napoletana was born in Naples in 1952, the year following the birth of the [[Sanremo Music Festival]].\n\nAmong the protagonists of the Festival from 1952 to 1970 would be such Neapolitan singers as [[Sergio Bruni]], [[Aurelio Fierro]], [[Nunzio Gallo]], [[Maria Paris (singer)|Maria Paris]], [[Giacomo Rondinella]], [[Mario Abbate]], [[Gloria Christian]], [[Mario Trevi]], [[Fausto Cigliano]], [[Franco Ricci]], [[Mirna Doris]], [[Tony Astarita]], [[Mario Merola (singer)|Mario Merola]], [[Enzo Del Forno (singer)|Enzo Del Forno]], [[Peppino di Capri]], [[Gianni Nazzaro]], [[Nino Fiore]], [[Geg\u00e8 Di Giacomo]], [[Tullio Pane]], [[Peppino Gagliardi]], [[Giulietta Sacco]]. They would be joined by such singers from the [[Sanremo Festival]], as [[Carla Boni]], [[Wilma De Angelis]], [[Domenico Modugno]], [[Ornella Vanoni]], [[Claudio Villa]], [[Don Backy]], [[Giorgio Gaber]], {{illm|Julie (Italian singer)|lt=Julie|it|Julie (cantante)}}, [[Fred Bongusto]], [[Nilla Pizzi]], [[Oscar Carboni]], [[Betty Curtis]], [[Giorgio Consolini]], [[Tony Dallara]], [[Jula De Palma]], [[Johnny Dorelli]], [[Equipe 84]], [[Louiselle]], [[Los Marcellos Ferial]], [[Marino Marini (musician)|Marino Marini]], [[Miranda Martino]], [[Milva]], [[Gino Latilla]], [[Anna Identici]], [[Wilma Goich]], [[I Giganti]], [[Luciano Tajoli]], [[Teo Teocoli]], [[Achille Togliani]], [[Iva Zanicchi]], [[Carmen Villani]], [[Luciano Virgili]], [[Narciso Parigi]], [[Katyna Ranieri]], [[Flo Sandon's]], [[Lara Saint Paul]], [[Memo Remigi]], [[Dean Reed]], [[Anna German]], [[Mei Lang Chang]], [[Nini Rosso]], [[Robertino]], [[Teddy Reno]] and authors as [[Franco Franchi]], [[Oreste Lionello]], [[Nino Taranto]], [[Renato Rascel]], [[Ombretta Colli]], [[Lando Fiorini]], [[Beniamino Maggio]], and [[Angela Luce]].\n\nAs presenters the festival would see, over the years, such people as [[Nunzio Filogamo]], [[Enzo Tortora]], [[Pippo Baudo]], [[Mike Bongiorno]], [[Corrado Mantoni|Corrado]], [[Daniele Piombi]].<ref>*Ettore De Mura, ''[[Enciclopedia della canzone napoletana]]'', [[Napoli]], Il Torchio, 1969</ref>\n\nInterrupted in 1971,<ref>[http://www.interviu.it/canzone/festival.htm ''Festival di Napoli '81'', Salvatore Palomba, La Canzone Napoletana, Ed. L'ancora del Mediterraneo - Napoli 2001]</ref> after many organizational efforts it returned to the city in 1981, taking the name \"Festival di Napoli '81\". The show, divided into three nights and organized by DAN with the help from [[RAI]] and the patronage of the [[Campania|Campania Region]], was presented by [[Franco Sulfites]], assisted by Maria Laura Soldano, and broadcast in full color from the Metropolitan Theatre of Naples on the television channel [[Rai Tre]] from 22.30 until the end. It was also broadcast on the radio on Rai's second station from 22.45.\n\nAfter that edition, the Festival, once again, was interrupted for a long period of time. In 1998 it returned, though with a different spirit and different results, on [[Rete 4]] and was held regularly until 2004, when it ceased again.<ref>''Enciclopedia del Festival della canzone napoletana 1952-1981'' di Antonio Sciotti (Ed. Luca Torre), 2011</ref>\n\n== Winners ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!width=\"100\" | Year\n!width=\"300\" | Artist\n!width=\"200\" | Song\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1952|1952]]\n| [[Nilla Pizzi]] and [[Franco Ricci]]\n| \"Desiderio 'e Sole\"\n|- \n| 1953\n| colspan=\"2\"     | ''The Festival di Napoli was not held this year.  See Note 1 below.''\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1954|1954]]\n| [[Tullio Pane]] and [[Achille Togliani]]\n| \"Suonno d'ammore\"\t\t\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1955|1955]]\n| [[Gino Latilla]] with [[Carla Boni]] and [[Maria Paris (singer)|Maria Paris]]\n| \"'E stelle 'e Napule\"\t\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1956|1956]]\n| [[Grazia Gresi]] and [[Aurelio Fierro]]\n| \"Guaglione\"\t\t\n|- \n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1957|1957]]\n| [[Marisa Del Frate]]\n| \"Malinconico autunno\"\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1958|1958]]\n| [[Nunzio Gallo]] and [[Aurelio Fierro]]\n| \"Vurria\"\t\t\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1959|1959]]\n| [[Fausto Cigliano]] and [[Teddy Reno]]\n| \"Sarr\u00e0 chi sa?\"\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1960|1960]]\n| [[Ruggero Cori]] and [[Flo Sandon's]]\n| \"Serenata a Margellina\"\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1961|1961]]\n| [[Aurelio Fierro]] and [[Betty Curtis]]\n| \"Tu si' 'a malincunia\"\t\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1962|1962]]\n| [[Sergio Bruni]] and [[Gloria Christian]]\n| \"Marechiaro marechiaro\"\t\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1963|1963]]\n| [[Claudio Villa (singer)|Claudio Villa]] and [[Maria Paris (singer)|Maria Paris]]\n| \"Jammo ja'\"\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1964|1964]]\n| [[Domenico Modugno]] and [[Ornella Vanoni]]\n| \"Tu si' 'na cosa grande\"\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1965|1965]]\n| [[Aurelio Fierro]] and [[Tony Astarita]]\n| \"Serenata all'acqua 'e mare\"\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1966|1966]]\n| [[Sergio Bruni]] and [[Robertino]]\n| \"Bella\"\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1967|1967]]\n| [[Nino Taranto]] and [[I Balordi]]\n| \"'O matusa\"\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1968|1968]]\n| [[Mirna Doris]] and [[Tony Astarita]]\n| \"Core spezzato\"\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1969|1969]]\n| [[Aurelio Fierro]] and [[Mirna Doris]]\n| \"Preghiera a 'na mamma\"\t\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1970|1970]]\n| [[Peppino di Capri]] and [[Gianni Nazzaro]]\n| \"Me chiamme ammore\"\n|- \n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1971|1971]]\n| colspan=\"2\"     | ''The Festival di Napoli was not held this year.  See Note 2 below.''\n|-\n| [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1981|1981]]\n| [[Mario Da Vinci]]\n| \"'A mamma\"\n|-\n| 1998\n| [[Ylenia (singer)|Ylenia]]\n| \"Ehi Pasc\u00e0!\"\n|-\n| 1999\n| [[Gianni Fiorellino]]\n| \"Girasole\"\n|-\n| 2000\n| [[Pia Paterno]]\n| \"Sempre con te\"\n|-\n| 2001\n| [[Mario Merola (singer)|Mario]] and [[Francesco Merola]]\n| \"L'urdemo emigrante\"\n|-\n| 2002\n| [[Anna Calemme]] e gli Istentales\n| \"Vorrei\"\n|-\n| 2003\n| [[Roberto Polisano]]\n| \"Amore senza parole\"\n|-\n| 2004\n| [[Marika (singer)|Marika]]\n| \"Astrigneme\"\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Notes ===\n\nNote 1: In 1953, the Festival was not held because it was initially designed to be [[wikt:biennial|biennial]] (every other year), but the Organization later reconsidered.\n\nNote 2: In [[:it:Festival di Napoli 1971|1971]], the Festival was not held because it was suspended by [[RAI]].\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Canzone Napoletana]]\n*[[List of historic rock festivals|List of historic rock and pop festivals]]\n*[[List of music festivals in Italy]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Historic rock festivals}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Traditional music]]\n[[Category:Music in Naples]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in Italy]]\n[[Category:Music festivals established in 1952]]\n[[Category:Pop music festivals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox music festival\n| name         = Festival della Canzone Napoletana<br>(Festival of Neapolitan Song)\n| image        = File:Ornella Vanoni al Festival di Napoli 1964.jpg\n| caption      = [[Ornella Vanoni]] at the festival in 1964\n| location     = [[Italy]]\n| years_active = 1952\u20131971<br>1981<br>1998\u20132004\n| founders     = [[RAI]]\n| dates        =\n| genre        = [[Neapolitan song]], [[folk music]], [[classical music]], [[pop music]], [[rock music]], etc.\n| attendance   = \n| capacity     =\n| website      =\n}}\nThe '''Festival della Canzone Napoletana''' (\"Festival of Neapolitan Song\"), commonly known as the '''Festival di Napoli''', is a [[Neapolitan song]] contest. The first edition was held in 1952 and the last in 2004. From 1952 to 1970 the show was broadcast on [[RAI]] and from 1998 to 2004, in a differently spirited version, by [[Rete 4]].\n\n== History ==\nA symbol of [[Neapolitan song]] of the second half of the twentieth century, the Festival della Canzone Napoletana was born in Naples in 1952, the year following the birth of the [[Sanremo Music Festival]].\n\nAmong the protagonists of the Festival from 1952 to 1970 would be such Neapolitan singers as [[Sergio Bruni]], [[Aurelio Fierro]], [[Nunzio Gallo]], [[Maria Paris (singer)|Maria Paris]], [[Giacomo Rondinella]], [[Mario Abbate]], [[Gloria Christian]], [[Mario Trevi]], [[Fausto Cigliano]], [[Franco Ricci]], [[Mirna Doris]], [[Tony Astarita]], [[Mario Merola (singer)|Mario Merola]], [[Enzo Del Forno (singer)|Enzo Del Forno]], [[Peppino di Capri]], [[Gianni Nazzaro]], [[Nino Fiore]], [[Geg\u00e8 Di Giacomo]], [[Tullio Pane]], [[Peppino Gagliardi]], [[Giulietta Sacco]]. They would be joined by such singers from the [[Sanremo Festival]], as [[Carla Boni]], [[Wilma De Angelis]], [[Domenico Modugno]], [[Ornella Vanoni]], [[Claudio Villa]], [[Don Backy]], [[Giorgio Gaber]], {{illm|Julie (Italian singer)|lt=Julie|it|Julie (cantante)}}, [[Fred Bongusto]],