{"title_page": "Festival dei Due Mondi", "text_new": "{{Music of Italy}}\n:''For the Spoleto Festival USA, see [[Spoleto Festival USA]] and for the Spoleto Festival Melbourne see [[Melbourne International Arts Festival]]''.\n\nThe '''''Festival dei Due Mondi''''' '''(Festival of the Two Worlds)''' is an annual summer music and [[opera]] festival held each June to early July in [[Spoleto]], Italy, since its founding by composer [[Gian Carlo Menotti]] in 1958. It features a vast array of concerts, opera, dance, drama, visual arts and roundtable discussions on science.\n\nThe \"Two Worlds\" in the name of the festival comes from Gian Carlo Menotti's intention to have the worlds of American and European culture facing each other in his event; this concept would then be strengthened by the fact that it was held in conjunction with its \"twin\", the [[Spoleto Festival USA]] held annually in May/June in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]. That twinning lasted some 15 years and, after growing disputes between the Menotti family and the board of Spoleto Festival USA, in the early 1990s a separation occurred. Under Menotti's direction in 1986, a third installment in the Spoleto Festival series was held in [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. Melbourne's Spoleto Festival changed its name to the [[Melbourne International Arts Festival|Melbourne International Festival of the Arts]] in 1990.\n\nFollowing Menotti's death in 2007, changes occurred in the administration with the result that the Italian Minister of Cultural Affairs appointed a new Artistic Administrator who continues to run the Festival.\n\n==The Italian Festival's location and activities==\nBecause Spoleto was a small town, where real estate and other goods and services were at the time relatively inexpensive, and also because there are two indoor theatres, a Roman theatre, and many other spaces, it was chosen by Menotti as the venue for an arts festival. It is also fairly close to Rome, with good rail connections.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Changes in administration==\nFollowing Menotti's death in February 2007, the city administrations of Spoleto and Charleston started talks to re-unite the two festivals, which resulted in the Mayor of Spoleto, Massimo Brunini, attending the opening ceremony of Spoleto Festival USA in May 2008.\n\nHowever, at the time of the 2007 Festival, the President and Artistic Director was Menotti's adopted son, [[Francis Menotti|Francis \"Chip\" Menotti]] and, in the fall of 2007, the Italian Minister of Cultural Affairs, [[Francesco Rutelli]]\u2014after unsuccessful negotiations with Menotti\u2014removed him from his position<ref>Wakin, ''New York Times''</ref> and named Giorgio Ferrara new artistic director of the festival. This has resulted in continuing controversy between representatives of the \"old\" and \"new\" managements of the Festival, as exemplified by the maintenance of a website critical of the former management, which can be seen below.\n\n==Prominent artists who have been involved==\n{{colbegin}}\n*[[Luchino Visconti]]\n*[[Eduardo De Filippo]]\n*[[Rudolf Nureyev]]\n*[[Carla Fracci]]\n*[[Thomas Schippers]]\n*[[Romolo Valli]] \n*[[Ken Russell]]\n*[[Nino Rota]]\n*[[Roman Polanski]] \n*[[Ezra Pound]]\n*[[Vittorio Gassman]] \n*[[Arnoldo Fo\u00e0]]\n*[[Luciano Pavarotti]]\n*[[Joaquin Cortes]]\n*[[Ralph Farris]]\n*[[Al Pacino]]\n*[[Marisa Berenson]] \n{{colend}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of opera festivals]]\n*[[Francis Menotti]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n*Daniel Wakin, [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/06/27/festival-of-two-worlds-the-menottis-are-history/ \"Spoleto Italy: The Menottis Are History\"], '''The New York Times'', June 27, 2008.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.festivaldispoleto.it/ Official website of the present ''Festival dei Due mondi'']\n*[http://www.spoletofestival.it/ Pre-2008 Festival management's website]\n\n{{Gian Carlo Menotti}}\n{{coord|42.73578|N|12.73527|E|type:landmark_region:IT|display=title|name=Teatro Nuovo, base of the Festival dei Due Mondi}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Music festivals in Italy|Due Mondi]]\n[[Category:Opera festivals]]\n[[Category:Summer festivals]]\n[[Category:Spoleto]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Umbria]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1958]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Music of Italy}}\n:''For the Spoleto Festival USA, see [[Spoleto Festival USA]] and for the Spoleto Festival Melbourne see [[Melbourne International Arts Festival]]''.\n\nThe '''''Festival dei Due Mondi''''' '''(Festival of the Two Worlds)''' is an annual summer music and [[opera]] festival held each June to early July in [[Spoleto]], Italy, since its founding by composer [[Gian Carlo Menotti]] in 1958. It features a vast array of concerts, opera, dance, drama, visual arts and roundtable discussions on science.\n\nThe \"Two Worlds\" in the name of the festival comes from Gian Carlo Menotti's intention to have the worlds of American and European culture facing each other in his event; this concept would then be strengthened by the fact that it was held in conjunction with its \"twin\", the [[Spoleto Festival USA]] held annually in May/June in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]. That twinning lasted some 15 years and, after growing disputes between the Menotti family and the board of Spoleto Festival USA, in the early 1990s a separation occurred. Under Menotti's direction in 1986, a third installment in the Spoleto Festival series was held in [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. Melbourne's Spoleto Festival changed its name to the [[Melbourne International Arts Festival|Melbourne International Festival of the Arts]] in 1990.\n\nFollowing Menotti's death in 2007, changes occurred in the administration with the result that the Italian Minister of Cultural Affairs appointed a new Artistic Administrator who continues to run the Festival.\n\n==The Italian Festival's location and activities==\nBecause Spoleto was a small town, where real estate and other goods and services were at the time relatively inexpensive, and also because there are two indoor theatres, a Roman theatre, and many other spaces, it was chosen by Menotti as the venue for an arts festival. It is also fairly close to Rome, with good rail connections.{{cn|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Changes in administration==\nFollowing Menotti's death in February 2007, the city administrations of Spoleto and Charleston started talks to re-unite the two festivals, which resulted in the Mayor of Spoleto, Massimo Brunini, attending the opening ceremony of Spoleto Festival USA in May 2008.\n\nHowever, at the time of the 2007 Festival, the President and Artistic Director was Menotti's adopted son, [[Francis Menotti|Francis \"Chip\" Menotti]] and, in the fall of 2007, the Italian Minister of Cultural Affairs, [[Francesco Rutelli]]\u2014after unsuccessful negotiations with Menotti\u2014removed him from his position<ref>Wakin, ''New York Times''</ref> and named Giorgio Ferrara new artistic director of the festival. This has resulted in continuing controversy between representatives of the \"old\" and \"new\" managements of the Festival, as exemplified by the maintenance of a website critical of the former management, which can be seen below.\n\n==Prominent artists who have been involved==\n{{colbegin}}\n*[[Luchino Visconti]]\n*[[Eduardo De Filippo]]\n*[[Rudolf Nureyev]]\n*[[Carla Fracci]]\n*[[Thomas Schippers]]\n*[[Romolo Valli]] \n*[[Ken Russell]]\n*[[Nino Rota]]\n*[[Roman Polanski]] \n*[[Ezra Pound]]\n*[[Vittorio Gassman]] \n*[[Arnoldo Fo\u00e0]]\n*[[Luciano Pavarotti]]\n*[[Joaquin Cortes]]\n*[[Ralph Farris]]\n*[[Al Pacino]]\n*[[Marisa Berenson]] \n{{colend}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of opera festivals]]\n*[[Francis Menotti]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n*Daniel Wakin, [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/06/27/festival-of-two-worlds-the-menottis-are-history/ \"Spoleto Italy: The Menottis Are History\"], '''The New York Times'', June 27, 2008.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.festivaldispoleto.it/ Official website of the present ''Festival dei Due mondi'']\n*[http://www.spoletofestival.it/ Pre-2008 Festival management's website]\n\n{{Gian Carlo Menotti}}\n{{coord|42.73578|N|12.73527|E|type:landmark_region:IT|display=title|name=Teatro Nuovo, base of the Festival dei Due Mondi}}\n\n[[Category:Music festivals in Italy|Due Mondi]]\n[[Category:Opera festivals]]\n[[Category:Summer festivals]]\n[[Category:Spoleto]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Umbria]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1958]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in Italy]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Festival_dei_Due_Mondi"}
{"title_page": "Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian music industry organization}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name         = Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana\n|image        = FIMI logo.png\n|image_border =\n|size         = 200px\n|caption      =\n|map          =\n|msize        =\n|mcaption     =\n|motto        =\n|formation    = 1992\n|extinction   =\n|type         = \n|headquarters = [[Milan]]\n|location     = Italy\n|membership   =\n|language     =\n|leader_title = Chairman\n|leader_name  = Enzo Mazza\n|key_people   =\n|num_staff    =\n|budget       =\n|website      = [http://www.fimi.it/ fimi.it]\n}}\n{{Music of Italy}}\n\nThe '''Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana''' ('''FIMI''') is an umbrella organization that keeps track of virtually all aspects of the music recording industry in [[Italy]]. It was established in 1992, when major corporate labels left the previously existing Associazione dei Fonografici Italiani (AFI).<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1992/ottobre/25/Sanremo_gia_una_stonatura_co_0_9210257836.shtml | work= [[Corriere della Sera]] | language = Italian | author = Mario Luzzatto Fegiz | date = 25 October 1992 | title = Sanremo '93, gi\u00e0 una stonatura}}</ref><ref name=\"Rockol2002\"/> During the following years, most of the remaining Italian record labels left AFI to join the new organization.<ref name=\"Rockol2002\"/> As of 2011, FIMI represents 2,500 companies operating in the [[music business]].<ref name=\"FIMI\"/>\n\nFIMI is a member of the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] and of the Italian employers' federation, [[Confindustria]].<ref name=\"FIMI\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.fimi.it/profilo.php | publisher = Federation of the Italian Music Industry | accessdate = 17 August 2011 | title = FIMI \u2013 Profilo | language = Italian | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110810170223/http://www.fimi.it/profilo.php | archivedate = 10 August 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Its main purpose is to protect the interests of the Italian record industry.<ref name=\"FIMI\"/>\n\nStarting in March 1995, the Italian Music Industry Federation began providing the Italian official albums chart. In January 1997, FIMI also became the provider of the Italian official singles chart. Due to the decrease of [[CD single]]s sales in Italy, FIMI replaced its physical singles chart with a [[music download|digital download]]s chart\u2014based on legal internet and mobile downloads\u2014on January 1, 2008.<ref name=Billboard>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003696014 |title=Italy's Singles Chart Goes Digital |accessdate=11 February 2008 |last=Worden |first=Mark |date=14 January 2008 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, Enzo Mazza was confirmed as FIMI chairman.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.rockol.it/news-273865/FIMI-nella-continuit%C3%A0,-Enzo-Mazza-riconfermato-presidente- | publisher = Rockol.it | accessdate =17 August 2011 | title = FIMI nella continuit\u00e0, Enzo Mazza riconfermato presidente | date = 29 July 2011 | language = Italian}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n\n===FIMI Albums Chart===\nIn September 1994, the chairman of FIMI, Caccia Dominioni, announced the Federation's intention to establish an album chart to replace the previously existing charts, which were considered unreliable due to their compiling methods.<ref name=\"First Article\">{{cite web | url = http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/settembre/16/arriva_nuova_hit_parade_mai_co_0_94091613662.shtml | work = [[Corriere della Sera]] | date = 16 September 1994 | author = Mario Luzzatto Fegiz | accessdate =17 August 2011 | title = Arriva la nuova hit parade: mai pi\u00f9 errori o trucchi | language = Italian}}</ref>\n\nThe Italian Music Industry Federation compiled its first album chart in March 1995. Issued on 7 March 1995, it was based on sales between 23 February 1995 and 1 March 1995.<ref name=\"LaStampa\">{{Cite web | url = http://archivio.lastampa.it/LaStampaArchivio/main/History/tmpl_viewObj.jsp?objid=1379638 | title = La nuova hit parade trasparente rivoluziona la classifica festivaliera. Sanremo, i veri vincitori. Volano alto i Neri per Caso e Fiorello | work = [[La Stampa]] | language = Italian | accessdate = 17 August 2011 | author = Marinella Venegoni | date = 7 March 1995 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120328215611/http://archivio.lastampa.it/LaStampaArchivio/main/History/tmpl_viewObj.jsp?objid=1379638 | archivedate = 28 March 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> This period coincided with the first week of sales for the albums released by the [[Sanremo Music Festival|45th Sanremo Music Festival]] contestants, the most important music event in Italy. The first number-one album was [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s ''[[Greatest Hits (Bruce Springsteen album)|Greatest Hits]]''.<ref name=\"LaStampa\"/>\n\nBetween 1995 and 2009, the FIMI Album Chart was based on data provided by [[Nielsen Company|Nielsen]]. From January 2010, the FIMI Album Chart's positions have been derived from [[GfK|GfK Retail and Technology Italia]] sales data. The chairman of the Italian Music Industry Federation, Enzo Mazza, explained this decision declaring that \"the long-time partnership with Nielsen, started in 1995, was satisfying, but in a moment marked by a deep transformation and innovation of the market, we thought that the service offered by Nielsen was no more adequate\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rockol.it/news-104848/Classifiche,-dal-2010-FIMI-cambia-partner-%28da-Nielsen-a-GfK%29 | publisher = Rockol.it | accessdate =17 August 2011 | title = Classifiche, dal 2010 FIMI cambia partner (da Nielsen a GfK) | date = 2 December 2009 | language = Italian}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, the chart was based on data digitally gathered by 130 sellers.<ref name=\"Articolo Repubblica\">{{cite web | url = http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1995/03/07/un-auditel-per-dischi.html | work = [[la Repubblica]] | accessdate =17 August 2011 | title = Un Auditel per i dischi | date = 7 March 1995 | author = Antonio Dipollina | language = Italian}}</ref> The number of sellers was later increased and, as of 2011, the chart is based on the number of copies sold between Monday to Sunday by a subset of 3,400 retailers.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fimi.it/gfk_notametodologica.php | publisher = Italian Music Industry Federation | accessdate = 17 August 2011 | title = Nota metodologica GfK Retail and Technology | language = Italian | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110819085449/http://www.fimi.it/gfk_notametodologica.php | archivedate = 19 August 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Starting from 14 October 2011, the FIMI Albums Chart also includes digital sales.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.fimi.it/dett_comunicatistampa.php?id=194 | publisher = Italian Music Industry Federation | language = Italian | accessdate = 10 October 2011 | title = Rivoluzione chart ufficiali FIMI/GfK: Entrano in Top Ten anche gli album digitali | date = 10 October 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111016033406/http://www.fimi.it/dett_comunicatistampa.php?id=194 | archivedate = 16 October 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===FIMI Compilations Chart===\nIn March 1995, alongside the FIMI Album Chart, the Italian Music Industry Federation also began the FIMI Compilations Chart, listing the best-selling albums by various artists. These albums are not included in the FIMI Album Chart.<ref name=\"Articolo Repubblica\"/> The first number-one was ''Sanremo '95'', released by RTI Music and featuring some of the songs performed during the 45th Sanremo Music Festival.<ref name=\"LaStampa\"/>\n\n===FIMI Singles Chart===\nIn January 1997, the Italian Music Industry Federation also started an official singles chart.<ref name=\"Rockol2002\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.rockol.it/news-49125/Inchiesta-classifiche-Rockol--la-parola-a-Enzo-Mazza-%28FIMI%29 | publisher = rockol.it | accessdate =17 August 2011 | title = Inchiesta classifiche Rockol: la parola a Enzo Mazza (FIMI) | language = Italian | date = 26 November 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=9 November 1996|title=Italian Music Biz Relaunches CD Single|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media]]|volume=108|issue=45|page=43|issn=0006-2510}}</ref><ref name=\"numberOneSingles\">{{Cite web | url = http://it-charts.150m.com/numeriuno-2000.htm | publisher = it-charts.150m.com | language = Italian | title = Singoli \u2013 I numeri uno dal 1997 al 2006 | accessdate = 17 August 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131003044052/http://it-charts.150m.com/numeriuno-2000.htm | archivedate = 3 October 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The first number-one single was [[Depeche Mode]]'s \"[[Barrel of a Gun (Depeche Mode song)|Barrel of a Gun]]\".<ref name=\"numberOneSingles\"/> Compiled by [[Nielsen Media Research|Nielsen]],<ref name=\"Rockol2002\"/> the chart listed the best-selling physical singles in Italy, but on 1 January 2008 it was replaced by the Top Digital Download, listing the best-selling digital singles.<ref name=Billboard/> The last number one on the physical FIMI Singles Chart was \"The Singles Collection\" by [[Vasco Rossi]].<ref name=\"Corriere030108\"/>\n\n===FIMI DVD Chart===\nThe Italian DVD Chart was established by the Italian Music Industry Federation in October 2003. The first Italian DVD Chart listed only the first ten positions, and was headed by [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]'s ''Inside the Songs of Sacred''.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2003/ottobre/15/hit_dei_dvd_musicali_Sting_co_0_031015085.shtml | work = [[Corriere della Sera]] | language = Italian | accessdate =17 August 2008 | date = 15 October 2003 | title = La hit dei dvd musicali: Sting al primo posto poi Mina e Pink Floyd}}</ref> As of July 2011, it lists the 20 best-selling music DVDs in Italy, and is compiled by [[ACNielsen]].<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.fimi.it/classifiche_result_dvd.php?anno=%202011&mese=07&id=359 | publisher = Italian Music Industry Federation | language = Italian | accessdate = 17 August 2011 | title = DVD Musicali \u2013 Classifica settimanale dal 25/07/2011 al 31/07/2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120512100504/http://www.fimi.it/classifiche_result_dvd.php?anno=%202011&mese=07&id=359 | archive-date = 12 May 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n===Top Digital Download===\nOn 10 April 2006, FIMI published the first chart listing the best-selling digital singles in Italy.<ref name=\"Repubblica2006\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.repubblica.it/2006/03/sezioni/scienza_e_tecnologia/musicadigit/gianna-nannini/gianna-nannini.html | work = [[la Repubblica]] | accessdate =17 August 2011 | date = 10 April 2006 | title = Gianna Nannini in testa alla hit della prima classifica del web | language = Italian}}</ref> Compiled by [[Nielsen SoundScan]], the chart was based on data provided by 10 digital stores.<ref name=\"Repubblica2006\"/> The first number-one single was \"Sei nell'anima\" by [[Gianna Nannini]].<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.lastampa.it/_web/cmstp/tmplrubriche/musica/grubrica.asp?ID_blog=37&ID_articolo=117&ID_sezione=62 | title = Gianna Nannini \u00e8 \"nell\u2019anima\" e in testa a ogni hit | work = [[La Stampa]] | accessdate = 17 August 2011 | language = Italian | date = 11 April 1996 | author = Marinella Venegoni }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nDue to the decrease of CD singles sales in Italy, on 1 January 2008 the Top Digital Download became the Italian official singles chart, replacing the chart based on physical sales.<ref name=Billboard/><ref name=\"Corriere030108\">{{Cite web | url = http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2008/gennaio/03/Una_rivoluzione_nella_musica_Addio_co_9_080103447.shtml | work = [[Corriere della Sera]] | language = Italian|  title = Una rivoluzione nella musica Addio alla hit dei cd \"singoli\" | author = Andrea Laffranchi | date = 3 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Sales certification==\nA certification system has existed in Italy since the mid 1970s. During that period, albums had to sell 500,000 units to qualify for a Silver status, while for Gold, the requirement was 1,000,000 units.<ref name=\"Silver/Gold awards 1974\">{{cite magazine|title=Billboard Vol. 86, No. 52|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hAkEAAAAMBAJ&q=%22italy%22+%22no+Silver+disk+for+singles%22 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|page=40|date=1974-12-26|accessdate=2013-04-29}}</ref> Singles, similarly, were required to sell 1,000,000 units to reach the Gold level in the mid 1970s.<ref name=\"Silver/Gold awards 1974\"/> Sales requirements for music recordings in Italy for domestic and international repertoire are the same levels.\n\n===Albums===\n\nNote that in the table below are the certification-levels, when the program of Gold and Platinum is operated under FIMI.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Period\n! Gold<br/>certification\n! Platinum<br/>certification\n! Diamond<br/>certification\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Until 31 December 2004<ref name=\"FIMI Certification-award-levels before February 2005\">{{cite web |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=XBQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA45&dq=FIMI++Platinum+from+100,000+to+80,000+2005&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Italian Labels Body FIMI |date=5 February 2005|work=[[Billboard magazine]]|accessdate=21 February 2012 | author = Mark Worden}}</ref><ref name=RockolCertifications2005>{{Cite web | url = http://www.rockol.it/news-68272/Calano-le-vendite,-la-FIMI-abbassa-la-soglia-di-dischi-d%27oro-e-di-platino |publisher = Rockol.it | language = Italian | accessdate =21 February 2012 | title = Calano le vendite, la FIMI abbassa la soglia di dischi d'oro e di platino | date = 14 January 2005}}</ref><ref name=cert2008>{{cite web |url= http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/global/1313783/fimi-lowers-gold-platinum-levels|title=FIMI Lowers Gold, Platinum Levels |date=25 January 2008|author=Mark Worden|work=billboard.biz |accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>\n|50,000\n|100,000\n|500,000\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 January 2005 to 31 December 2007<ref name=RockolCertifications2005/><ref name=cert2008/>\n|40,000\n|80,000\n|400,000\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 January 2008 to <!--\n\nPlease see the discussion on the talk-page. FIMI's site only states \"FIMI decided to formalize the process of certification of sales data published in Italy after January 1, 2009\". It doesn't support change in levels.-->late 2009<ref name=cert2008/><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.rockol.it/news-91912/Vendite-a-picco,-scendono-ancora-i-parametri-per-dischi-d%27oro-e-di-platino | publisher = Rockol.it | language = Italian|  accessdate =21 February 2012 | title = Vendite a picco, scendono ancora i parametri per dischi d'oro e di platino | date = 30 January 2008}}</ref>\n|35,000\n|70,000\n|350,000\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From late<!--\n\nPlease see the discussion on the talk-page. FIMI's site only states \"FIMI decided to formalize the process of certification of sales data published in Italy after January 1, 2009\". It doesn't support change in levels.--> 2009<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Pnp_Xu47q9cC&pg=PT30&dq=Italy+FIMI+2010#v=onepage&q=Italy%20FIMI%202010&f=false|title=Screen nDream| publisher =[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]|accessdate=6 March 2012|date=14 November 2009}}</ref> to 31 December 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/international-award-levels.pdf |title=IFPI Certification Awards Levels 2011 |publisher=IFPI |accessdate=10 November 2014 |date=2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726171640/http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/international-award-levels.pdf |archivedate=26 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ifpi.org/content/library/international-award-levels.pdf |title=IFPI Certification Awards Levels 2012 |publisher=IFPI |accessdate=10 November 2014 |date=2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120810090943/http://ifpi.org/content/library/international-award-levels.pdf |archivedate=10 August 2012 }}</ref>\n|30,000\n|60,000\n|300,000\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 January 2012<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fimi.it/cert_notametodologica_2012.php |publisher=Italian Music Industry Federation |language=Italian |accessdate=2 March 2016 |title=Assegnazioni dichi d'oro, platino, multi platino, diamond |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105164218/http://www.fimi.it/cert_notametodologica_2012.php |archivedate=5 January 2013 }}</ref>\n|30,000\n|60,000\n|600,000\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 January 2014<ref name=\"FIMI Profili: Certificazioni 2014\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fimi.it/certificazioni/ |publisher=Italian Music Industry Federation |language=Italian |accessdate=10 February 2015 |title=FIMI Profili: Certificazioni: CATEGORIE CERTIFICAZIONE ALBUM e COMPILATION (prodotto fisico e online) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210212350/http://www.fimi.it/certificazioni/ |archivedate=10 February 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|25,000\n|50,000\n|500,000\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\nItaly has had a Gold certification program for singles during the mid 1970s, with the level for Gold set at 1,000,000 units.<ref name=\"Silver/Gold awards 1974\"/> Even though, the requirement of 1,000,000 units for Gold was quite high for the Italian market, this program was carried on to the 1980s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Million selling records from the 1900s to the 1980s: an illustrated directory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5iIKAQAAMAAJ&q=%22italy%22+%221%2C000%2C000%22 |last=Murells|first=Joseph|publisher=Batsford|page=10|date=1984-12-31|accessdate=2013-04-29|isbn=9780713438437 }}</ref> The singles certification program was abandoned when FIMI took over the operations, and it wasn't until 1999 that Italy re-launched its Gold and Platinum program for singles.<ref name=cert1999>{{cite journal|magazine=Billboard|date=27 March 1999|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XQ0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA69&dq=FIMI%20%20Singles%20Certifications%201999&pg=PA69 |title=Newsline...: Italian Label's Body|page=69|volume=111|number=13|issn=0006-2510|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]], Inc.|author = Mark Dezzani}}</ref>\n\nNote that in the table below are the certification-levels, when the program of Gold and Platinum is operated under FIMI.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Period\n! Gold<br/>certification\n! Platinum<br/>certification\n! Diamond<br/>certification\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From March 1999 to 31 December 2004<ref name=cert1999/><ref name=cert2005>{{cite journal|magazine=Billboard|date=5 February 2005|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XBQEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA45&dq=FIMI%20Platinum%20levels&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q=FIMI%20Platinum%20levels&f=false|title=newsline.|page=45|volume=117|number=6|issn=0006-2510|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]], Inc.}}</ref>\n|25,000\n|50,000\n|N/A\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 January 2005 to 31 December 2009<ref name=RockolCertifications2005/><ref name=cert2008/><ref>{{cite web|title=IFPI Certification-levels 2009 |url=http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/certification-award-levels.pdf |publisher=IFPI |accessdate=2014-01-17 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304190545/http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/certification-award-levels.pdf |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref>\n|10,000\n|20,000\n|N/A\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 January 2010<ref>{{cite web|title=IFPI Certification-levels 2010 |url=http://ifpi.org/content/library/international-award-levels.pdf |publisher=IFPI |accessdate=2014-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126060430/http://ifpi.org/content/library/international-award-levels.pdf |archivedate=26 November 2010 }}</ref>\n|15,000\n|30,000\n|N/A\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 January 2014<ref name=\"FIMI Profili: Certificazioni 2014\"/>\n|15,000\n|30,000\n|300,000\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 February 2015<ref name=\"FIMI Profili: Certificazioni 2015\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fimi.it/certificazioni/ |publisher=Italian Music Industry Federation |language=Italian |accessdate=5 February 2015 |title=FIMI Profili: Certificazioni: CATEGORIE CERTIFICAZIONE SINGLE TRACK ONLINE |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210212350/http://www.fimi.it/certificazioni/ |archivedate=10 February 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|25,000\n|50,000\n|500,000\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 January 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fimi.it/news/novita-sul-fronte-delle-classifiche-di-vendita-fimi-gfk.kl |publisher=Italian Music Industry Federation |language=Italian |accessdate=26 December 2019 |title=Novit\u00e0 sul fronte delle classifiche di vendita FIMI/GfK |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226180136/https://www.fimi.it/news/novita-sul-fronte-delle-classifiche-di-vendita-fimi-gfk.kl |archivedate=26 December 2019 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|35,000\n|70,000\n|700,000\n|}\n\n===Music DVDs===\nNote that in the table below are the certification-levels, when the program of Gold and Platinum is operated under FIMI.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Period\n! Gold<br/>certification\n! Platinum<br/>certification\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|From 1 January 2005 to 31 December 2008<ref name=RockolCertifications2005/>\n|15,000\n|30,000\n|-\n|}\n\n==List of certified albums==\nThe following is a list of Platinum and multi-platinum albums that have been certified by the Italian Music Industry Federation. The listed certifications below can be verified through FIMI's certification database.<