l\" style=\"width:135px;\"| Certification-level<br /><small>(based on release date)</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Adele]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[21 (Adele album)|21]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[United Kingdom]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 25-01-2011<br /><small>(Week 52, 2013)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 480,000 units\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Tiziano Ferro]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[L'amore \u00e8 una cosa semplice]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Italy]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 28-11-2011<br /><small>(Week 52, 2013)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 480,000 units\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Tiziano Ferro]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[TZN - The Best of Tiziano Ferro]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Italy\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 25-11-2014<br /><small>(Week 15, 2017)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 400,000 units\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Diamond===\n\nNote that the albums released from 2005 until the end of 2011, were qualified for Diamond-award upon reaching five-times Platinum. FIMI, however, changed this rule in January 2012, and began to base the Diamond-award on ten-times Platinum for all titles released on/after January 1, 2012.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:122px;\"| Artist\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:122px;\"| Album\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:122px;\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:122px;\"| Release-date<br /><small>(certification date)</small>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:135px;\"| Certification-level<br /><small>(based on release date)</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Jovanotti]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Ora (Jovanotti album)|Ora]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Italy]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24-01-2011<br /><small>(Week 46, 2011)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 300,000 units\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Luciano Ligabue|Ligabue]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''Arrivederci, mostro''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Italy\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11-05-2010<br /><small>(Week 42, 2010)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 300,000 units\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Mod\u00e0]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''Viva i romantici''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Italy\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16-02-2011<br /><small>(Week 32, 2011)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 300,000 units\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Renato Zero]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''Zeronovetour presente''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Italy\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20-03-2009<br /><small>(Week 19, 2010)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 350,000 units\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Vasco Rossi]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''Tracks 2''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Italy\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 27-11-2009<br /><small>(Week 40, 2010)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 350,000 units\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Vasco Rossi\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''Vivere o niente''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Italy\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 29-03-2011<br /><small>(Week 19, 2011)</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 300,000 units\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of number-one hits (Italy)]]\n*''[[Musica e dischi]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fimi.it/ FIMI website]\n*[http://www.fimi.it/classifiche_search.php FIMI archives]\n*[http://www.italiancharts.com/ ItalianCharts.com \u2014 archives from 2000 onwards (top 20 positions only)]\n*[http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/hp_weeks/index.html Hit Parade Italia (Archives)]\n\n{{FIMI}}\n{{Record Charts}}\n\n[[Category:Music organisations based in Italy]]\n[[Category:Music industry associations]]\n[[Category:Italian record charts| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federazione_Industria_Musicale_Italiana"}
{"title_page": "M-134 (Michigan highway)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=MI\n|type=M\n|route=134\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=190|frame-lat=46.009277|frame-long=-84.212735|zoom=8|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/M-134 (Michigan highway)}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=M-134 highlighted in red, the ferry connection in blue\n|maint=[[Michigan Department of Transportation|MDOT]] and {{abbr|EUPTA| Eastern Upper Peninsula Transportation Authority}}\n|length_mi=50.233\n|length_ref=<ref name=PRFA/><ref name=CGI/>\n|length_notes=Length includes the ferry connection\n|established=1939<ref name=MSHD39-04/><ref name=MSHD39-12/>\n|tourist=[[File:Lake Huron Circle Tour.svg|20px|alt=|link=]][[File:Lake Huron Circle Tour brown.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] [[Lake Huron Circle Tour]] and Spur<br/>[[File:Pure Michigan Byway.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] M-134 North Huron Byway\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MI|I|75}} near [[Saint Ignace, Michigan|St. Ignace]]\n|junction={{jct|state=MI|M|129}} in [[Cedarville, Michigan|Cedarville]]<br>\n{{jct|state=MI|M|48}} south of [[Goetzville, Michigan|Goetzville]]\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b=Four Corners on [[Drummond Island, Michigan|Drummond Island]]\n|counties=[[Mackinac County, Michigan|Mackinac]], [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa]]\n|previous_type=M 1948\n|previous_route=132\n|next_type=M 1948\n|next_route=135\n|browse={{mi browse|previous_type=M|previous_route=3|route={{nowrap|M-4}}|next_type=M|next_route=4|next_dab=1979\u20131986}}\n}}\n'''M-134''' is an east\u2013west [[Michigan State Trunkline Highway System|state trunkline highway]] in the [[Upper Peninsula of Michigan|Upper Peninsula]] (UP) of the US state of [[Michigan]]. It connects [[Interstate 75 in Michigan|Interstate 75]] (I-75) north of [[St. Ignace, Michigan|St. Ignace]] with the communities of [[Hessel, Michigan|Hessel]], [[Cedarville, Michigan|Cedarville]] and [[De Tour Village, Michigan|De Tour Village]] along [[Lake Huron]]. East of De Tour, the highway crosses the [[De Tour Passage]] on a ferry to run south of the community of [[Drummond, Michigan|Drummond]] on [[Drummond Island, Michigan|Drummond Island]]. It is one of only three state trunklines in Michigan on islands; the others are [[M-154 (Michigan highway)|M-154]] on [[Harsens Island]] and [[M-185 (Michigan highway)|M-185]] on [[Mackinac Island]]. M-134 is also one of only two highways to utilize a ferry in Michigan; the other is [[U.S. Route 10 in Michigan|US Highway 10]] (US&nbsp;10) which crosses [[Lake Michigan]] from [[Manitowoc, Wisconsin]], to [[Ludington, Michigan|Ludington]]. Most of the mainland portion of M-134 is also part of the [[Lake Huron Circle Tour]], and since 2015, it has been a [[Pure Michigan Byway]] under the name '''M-134 North Huron Byway'''.\n\nA separate highway bore the M-134 designation in the [[Lower Peninsula of Michigan|Lower Peninsula]] from the late 1920s to the late 1930s. The current highway's immediate predecessors were included in the original '''M-4''' in the state. That designation was renumbered to the current M-134 moniker in 1939. Since the trunkline number was finalized, it was extended eastward to end south of [[Goetzville, Michigan|Goetzville]] in the 1950s, with a further extension to De Tour in the 1950s. The western section was moved closer to the lakeshore in the 1960s. The last change came when M-134 was extended to Drummond Island in 1989.\n\n==Route description==\nM-134 starts at the interchange for exit&nbsp;359 along I-75 north of St. Ignace in rural [[Mackinac County, Michigan|Mackinac County]] near the [[St. Martin Bay]] of Lake Huron. As the highway runs eastward, it carries the Lake Huron Circle Tour over the [[Pine River (Mackinac County, Michigan)|Pine River]] on Huron Shore Drive. The trunkline turns to the southeast and follows the shoreline along the bay and runs inland at the bases of the peninsulas that form the Search Bay. Returning to a shoreline routing at Mismer Bay, M-134 runs through the wooded rural areas into Hessel. There Huron Shore Drive continues eastward to Cedarville where the highway meets the south end of [[M-129 (Michigan highway)|M-129]] north of Marquette Island. Farther east, M-134 runs along the north side of the many small bays and channels that separate the [[Les Cheneaux Islands]] from the mainland.<ref name=\"MDOT10\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 2010 |sections=D10\u2013D12}}</ref><ref name=google>{{google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&source=s_d&saddr=M-134+W&daddr=M-134+E%2FE+Channel+Rd&hl=en&geocode=FbrFvgIdHMjz-g%3BFQ7jvQIdkD8C-w&mra=ls&sll=46.00507,-83.732643&sspn=0.055921,0.058193&ie=UTF8&t=h&z=9 |title=Overview Map of M-134 |accessdate=May 10, 2011}}</ref> About {{convert|6|mi}} west of Cedarville, M-134 crosses into [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa County]] for about a mile and a half (2.5&nbsp;km); the highway passes back into a sliver of Mackinac County that extends along the Lake Huron shoreline for another {{convert|5|mi}} before finally crossing back into Chippewa County.<ref name=PRFA/>\n\nNear Albany Harbor, M-134 follows Scenic Road to an intersection with [[M-48 (Michigan highway)|M-48]]. The main route of the Lake Michigan Circle Tour turns north on M-48 while a locally designed loop route continues east on M-134 along Lake Huron. The highway continues past [[De Tour State Park]] and St. Vital Point before heading northeasterly to De Tour Village. In the middle of the village, M-134 runs north on Ontario Street and turns east along Elizabeth Street to connect to the ferry docks; the loop tour continues north out of town on county roads. The highway uses the ferry, run by the regional public transportation agency, to cross the De Tour Passage. Once on Drummond Island, M-134 follows Channel Road northward along the passage before turning eastward. The trunkline cuts across to run along Sturgeon Bay on the north shore of the island. On the east side of the bay, M-134 turns inland and runs east to the Four Corners, south of the unincorporated community of Drummond. The trunkline terminates at that intersection south of the [[Drummond Island Airport]] where Channel, Townline, Johnswood, and Shore roads (west, north, east and south respectively) come together.<ref name=MDOT10/><ref name=google/> M-134 is one of three state highways in Michigan located on an island; the two other state highways located on islands are M-185 on Mackinac Island and M-154 on Harsens Island.<ref name=MDOT10I>{{cite MDOT map |year=2010 |sections=D10, L14}}</ref>\n\nNo part of M-134 is listed on the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]],<ref name=NHS-MI>{{cite map|author=Michigan Department of Transportation |location=Lansing |scale=Scale not given |title=National Highway System, Michigan |date=April 23, 2006 |publisher=Michigan Department of Transportation |url=http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Statewide_150626_7.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=October 7, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004040152/http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Statewide_150626_7.pdf |archivedate=October 4, 2012 |df= }}</ref> a system of roadways important to the country's economy, defense, and mobility.<ref name=NHS>{{cite web |first1= Stefan |last1= Natzke |first2= Mike |last2= Neathery |first3= Kevin |last3= Adderly |url= http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/ |title= What is the National Highway System? |work= National Highway System |publisher= [[Federal Highway Administration]] |date= June 20, 2012 |accessdate= July 1, 2012 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> In 2009, the [[Michigan Department of Transportation]] (MDOT) conducted a survey to determine the traffic volume along the highway, reported using a metric called [[average annual daily traffic]] (AADT). The department determined that the highest count was the 3,595&nbsp;vehicles a day that used the highway west of the M-129 junction in Cedarville; the lowest counts were 608&nbsp;vehicles daily between the M-48 junction and the De Tour village limits. On the island, 667&nbsp;vehicles use M-134 daily.<ref name=TMIS>{{cite web |author= Bureau of Transportation Planning |url=http://mdotnetpublic.state.mi.us/tmispublic/ |title= Traffic Monitoring Information System |publisher=Michigan Department of Transportation |year=2008 |accessdate=May 10, 2011}}</ref> According to tourism officials in the area, over 100,000&nbsp;vehicles per year are transported round trip on the ferry with almost twice as many additional passengers.<ref name=ferry/>\n\n==Ferry==\n[[File:Drummond Island Ferry.jpg|thumb|300px|The SS ''Drummond Islander IV'' crossing the De Tour Passage near the MV ''American Mariner'']]\nThe Eastern Upper Peninsula Transportation Authority (EUPTA) operates the Drummond Island Ferry across the De Tour Passage in addition to two other ferries and the regional rural bus system for [[Luce County, Michigan|Luce]] and Chippewa counties.<ref name=eupta>{{cite web |url=http://www.eupta.net/ |title=Index |publisher= Eastern Upper Transportation Authority |author=Staff |date= March 11, 2011 |accessdate= May 10, 2011}}</ref> As part of the service between De Tour and Drummond Island, EUPTA operates up to three different vessels: the SS ''Drummond Islander'', SS ''Drummond Islander III'' and the SS ''Drummond Islander IV''. {{As of|2011}}, fares start at $12 per car and increase based on the size of the vehicle transported, including a [[fuel surcharge]]. Passenger fares are $2 for adults and $1 for seniors or students; the vehicle driver's fare is included in the vehicle charge. Ferries leave Drummond Island at 10 minutes after the hour, from De Tour at 20 minutes to the hour, and run most of the day; some crossing times are only operated seasonally.<ref name=ferry>{{cite web |url= http://www.drummondislandchamber.com/index.php?page=Transportation |title= Drummond Island Transportation: Ferry and Airport |publisher= Drummond Island Tourism Association |year= 2011 |author= Staff |accessdate= May 10, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110616051901/http://www.drummondislandchamber.com/index.php?page=Transportation |archive-date= June 16, 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> M-134 is one of two highways in Michigan to use a ferry connection; the other is US&nbsp;10 between Ludington, Michigan, and Manitowoc, Wisconsin.<ref name=MDOT10F>{{cite MDOT map |year= 2010 |sections=I5\u2013I7}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nStarting in late 1928 or early 1929, the first route designated as M-134 was a road in [[Missaukee County, Michigan|Missaukee County]] from [[M-66 (Michigan highway)|M-66]] three miles (4.8&nbsp;km) north of [[McBain, Michigan|McBain]] east to [[Falmouth, Michigan|Falmouth]] in the [[Northern Michigan|northern Lower Peninsula]].<ref name=MSHD28-10>{{cite MDOT map |date=1928-10-01 }}</ref><ref name=MSHD29-05>{{cite MDOT map |date=1929-05-01 }}</ref> In 1938, the [[Michigan State Highway Department]] (MSHD) returned the road to local control.<ref name=MSHD38-05>{{cite MDOT map |date=1938-05-01 |section=H10}}</ref><ref name=MSHD38-12>{{cite MDOT map |date=1938-12-01 |section=H10}}</ref>\n\nWhen the rest of the state highway system was first designated,<ref name=press-1919-09-20>{{cite news |title=Michigan May Do Well Following Wisconsin's Road Marking System |work=[[The Grand Rapids Press]] |date= September 20, 1919 |page=10}}</ref> by July 1, 1919, the first state highway in the area of today's M-134 was a section of [[M-12 (Michigan highway)|M-12]].<ref name=MSHD19UP>{{cite MDOT map |date= 1919-07-01U }}</ref> That highway segment was used for [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]] in 1926.<ref name=MSHD26-12>{{cite MDOT map |date=1926-12-01 }}</ref> A rerouting of US&nbsp;2 was completed in 1933 between [[Rogers Park, Michigan|Rogers Park]] and [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]]. The new routing followed [[Mackinac Trail]] instead of turning east to [[Cedarville, Michigan|Cedarville]] and north to Sault Ste. Marie. The former routing was given the [[M-121 (Michigan highway)|M-121]] designation,<ref name=MSHD33-05>{{cite MDOT map |date=1933-05-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref><ref name=MSHD33-09>{{cite MDOT map |date=1933-09-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref> and later M-4.<ref name=MSHD36-06>{{cite MDOT map |date=1936-06-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref>\n\nThe current designation appeared in the Upper Peninsula in 1939, soon after being removed from Missaukee County. It replaced the former M-4 route designation. At the time, M-134 was routed farther inland between US&nbsp;2 and a point north of Hessel. The highway ended at the Mackinac\u2013Chippewa county line, but an extension farther east was shown on maps of the time as under construction.<ref name=MSHD39-04>{{cite MDOT map |date=1939-04-15 |link= yes |c-link= yes |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref><ref name=MSHD39-12>{{cite MDOT map |date=1939-12-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref> This segment of roadway was completed in the latter half of 1940, extending M-134 to terminate at M-48 about {{convert|10|mi}} west of DeTour.<ref name=MSHD40-07>{{cite MDOT map |date=1940-07-15 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref><ref name=MSHD40-12>{{cite MDOT map |date=1940-12-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref> In 1950, a new roadway section was added to the state highway system, bypassing the former routing of M-48 west of DeTour; in the process the MSHD extended M-134 on this new highway and truncated M-48 to the junction south of [[Goetzville, Michigan|Goetzville]].<ref name=MSHD50-04>{{cite MDOT map |date=1950-04-15 |sections=D11\u2013D12}}</ref><ref name=MSHD50-07>{{cite MDOT map |date=1950-07-01 |sections=D11\u2013D12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1958, the highway west of Hessel was shifted to follow an alignment closer to Lake Huron; the MSHD transferred the former routing of M-134 to local control at that time.<ref name=MSHD57-10>{{cite MDOT map |date=1957-10-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref><ref name=MSHD58>{{cite MDOT map |year=1958 |sections= D10\u2013D11}}</ref> In October 1963, the final section of I-75/US&nbsp;2 freeway opened in the UP;<ref name=AP>{{cite news |title= Walking Grandfather Completes Long Hike |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=f1MvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IKsFAAAAIBAJ&pg=879,5833952&dq=interstate+75+freeway&hl=en |work=[[Argus-Press]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |location=Owosso, MI |date=October 31, 1963 |page=14 |accessdate= May 10, 2011 |via= [[Google News]] }}</ref> M-134's western terminus was truncated slightly to end at the new freeway instead of the former routing of US&nbsp;2 along [[Mackinac Trail]].<ref name=MSHD63>{{cite MDOT map |year=1963 |section=D10}}</ref><ref name=MSHD64>{{cite MDOT map |year=1964 |section=D10}}</ref> In 1989, MDOT extended the trunkline to add a segment on Drummond Island; in the process, the Drummond Island Ferry across the DeTour Passage was added to the route.<ref name=MDOT89>{{cite MDOT map |year=1989 |section=D12}}</ref><ref name=MDOT90>{{cite MDOT map |year=1990 |section=D12}}</ref> The entire length of the highway was dedicated as a [[Pure Michigan Byway]] on October 16, 2015.<ref name=M-134-FreePress>{{cite news |date= October 14, 2015 |title= M-134 in UP Tapped as Pure Michigan's First Byway |url= http://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2015/10/14/pure-michigan-first-byway-highway-134/73921032/ |work= [[Detroit Free Press]] |agency= [[Associated Press]] |access-date= October 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{MIinttop|ref=<ref name=PRFA>{{cite MDOT PRFA |link= yes |accessdate= May 10, 2011}}</ref><ref name=CGI>{{cite web |author= Michigan Center for Geographic Information |title= Geographic Data Library |date=May 2007 |publisher= [[Michigan Department of Information Technology]] |url= http://www.mcgi.state.mi.us/mgdl/?rel=thext&action=thmname&cid=14&cat=MI+Geographic+Framework+All+Roads+%28v7b%29| accessdate=May 11, 2011 }}</ref>}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Mackinac\n|cspan=2\n|location=St. Ignace Township\n|mile=0.000\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|I|75|Tour|LHCT|dir2=south|city1=St. Ignace|city2=Sault Ste. Marie}}\n|notes=Exit&nbsp;359 on I-75; western end of LHCT concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Cedarville\n|mile=17.007\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|129|city1=Pickford|city2=Sault Ste. Marie|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of M-129}}\n{{jctco|state=MI|county=Chippewa}}\n{{jctco|state=MI|county=Mackinac}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Chippewa\n|cspan=3\n|location=DeTour Township\n|type=concur\n|mile=31.139\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|48|Tour|LHCT|dir1=west|dir2=north|city1=Pickford}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of M-48; eastern end of LHCT concurrency mainline, spur route continues eastward}}\n{{jctbridge\n|location_special=[[DeTour Passage]]\n|mile=41.338\n|mile2=42.324\n|type=toll\n|bridge=[[File:Ferry Sign.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] Drummond Island Ferry (tolled)}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Drummond Township\n|mile=50.233\n|road=Four Corners\n|notes=}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur,toll}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Michigan Highways}}\n*[[SS Badger|SS ''Badger]], connects US&nbsp;10 across Lake Michigan\n*''[[Lake Express]]'', a modern ferry that follows a previous route that connected [[U.S. Route 16 in Michigan|US&nbsp;16]] across Lake Michigan\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n*[http://www.michiganhighways.org/listings/M-134.html M-134] at Michigan Highways\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M134}}\n[[Category:State highways in Michigan|134]]\n[[Category:Lake Huron Circle Tour]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Mackinac County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Chippewa County, Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=MI\n|type=M\n|route=134\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=240|frame-lat=46.009277|frame-long=-84.212735|zoom=8|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/M-134 (Michigan highway)}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=M-134 highlighted in red, the ferry connection in blue\n|maint=[[Michigan Department of Transportation|MDOT]] and {{abbr|EUPTA| Eastern Upper Peninsula Transportation Authority}}\n|length_mi=50.233\n|length_ref=<ref name=PRFA/><ref name=CGI/>\n|length_notes=Length includes the ferry connection\n|established=1939<ref name=MSHD39-04/><ref name=MSHD39-12/>\n|tourist=[[File:Lake Huron Circle Tour.svg|20px|alt=|link=]][[File:Lake Huron Circle Tour brown.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] [[Lake Huron Circle Tour]] and Spur<br/>[[File:Pure Michigan Byway.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] M-134 North Huron Byway\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=MI|I|75}} near [[Saint Ignace, Michigan|St. Ignace]]\n|junction={{jct|state=MI|M|129}} in [[Cedarville, Michigan|Cedarville]]<br>\n{{jct|state=MI|M|48}} south of [[Goetzville, Michigan|Goetzville]]\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b=Four Corners on [[Drummond Island, Michigan|Drummond Island]]\n|counties=[[Mackinac County, Michigan|Mackinac]], [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa]]\n|previous_type=M 1948\n|previous_route=132\n|next_type=M 1948\n|next_route=135\n|browse={{mi browse|previous_type=M|previous_route=3|route={{nowrap|M-4}}|next_type=M|next_route=4|next_dab=1979\u20131986}}\n}}\n'''M-134''' is an east\u2013west [[Michigan State Trunkline Highway System|state trunkline highway]] in the [[Upper Peninsula of Michigan|Upper Peninsula]] (UP) of the US state of [[Michigan]]. It connects [[Interstate 75 in Michigan|Interstate 75]] (I-75) north of [[St. Ignace, Michigan|St. Ignace]] with the communities of [[Hessel, Michigan|Hessel]], [[Cedarville, Michigan|Cedarville]] and [[De Tour Village, Michigan|De Tour Village]] along [[Lake Huron]]. East of De Tour, the highway crosses the [[De Tour Passage]] on a ferry to run south of the community of [[Drummond, Michigan|Drummond]] on [[Drummond Island, Michigan|Drummond Island]]. It is one of only three state trunklines in Michigan on islands; the others are [[M-154 (Michigan highway)|M-154]] on [[Harsens Island]] and [[M-185 (Michigan highway)|M-185]] on [[Mackinac Island]]. M-134 is also one of only two highways to utilize a ferry in Michigan; the other is [[U.S. Route 10 in Michigan|US Highway 10]] (US&nbsp;10) which crosses [[Lake Michigan]] from [[Manitowoc, Wisconsin]], to [[Ludington, Michigan|Ludington]]. Most of the mainland portion of M-134 is also part of the [[Lake Huron Circle Tour]], and since 2015, it has been a [[Pure Michigan Byway]] under the name '''M-134 North Huron Byway'''.\n\nA separate highway bore the M-134 designation in the [[Lower Peninsula of Michigan|Lower Peninsula]] from the late 1920s to the late 1930s. The current highway's immediate predecessors were included in the original '''M-4''' in the state. That designation was renumbered to the current M-134 moniker in 1939. Since the trunkline number was finalized, it was extended eastward to end south of [[Goetzville, Michigan|Goetzville]] in the 1950s, with a further extension to De Tour in the 1950s. The western section was moved closer to the lakeshore in the 1960s. The last change came when M-134 was extended to Drummond Island in 1989.\n\n==Route description==\nM-134 starts at the interchange for exit&nbsp;359 along I-75 north of St. Ignace in rural [[Mackinac County, Michigan|Mackinac County]] near the [[St. Martin Bay]] of Lake Huron. As the highway runs eastward, it carries the Lake Huron Circle Tour over the [[Pine River (Mackinac County, Michigan)|Pine River]] on Huron Shore Drive. The trunkline turns to the southeast and follows the shoreline along the bay and runs inland at the bases of the peninsulas that form the Search Bay. Returning to a shoreline routing at Mismer Bay, M-134 runs through the wooded rural areas into Hessel. There Huron Shore Drive continues eastward to Cedarville where the highway meets the south end of [[M-129 (Michigan highway)|M-129]] north of Marquette Island. Farther east, M-134 runs along the north side of the many small bays and channels that separate the [[Les Cheneaux Islands]] from the mainland.<ref name=\"MDOT10\">{{cite MDOT map |year= 2010 |sections=D10\u2013D12}}</ref><ref name=google>{{google maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&source=s_d&saddr=M-134+W&daddr=M-134+E%2FE+Channel+Rd&hl=en&geocode=FbrFvgIdHMjz-g%3BFQ7jvQIdkD8C-w&mra=ls&sll=46.00507,-83.732643&sspn=0.055921,0.058193&ie=UTF8&t=h&z=9 |title=Overview Map of M-134 |accessdate=May 10, 2011}}</ref> About {{convert|6|mi}} west of Cedarville, M-134 crosses into [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa County]] for about a mile and a half (2.5&nbsp;km); the highway passes back into a sliver of Mackinac County that extends along the Lake Huron shoreline for another {{convert|5|mi}} before finally crossing back into Chippewa County.<ref name=PRFA/>\n\nNear Albany Harbor, M-134 follows Scenic Road to an intersection with [[M-48 (Michigan highway)|M-48]]. The main route of the Lake Michigan Circle Tour turns north on M-48 while a locally designed loop route continues east on M-134 along Lake Huron. The highway continues past [[De Tour State Park]] and St. Vital Point before heading northeasterly to De Tour Village. In the middle of the village, M-134 runs north on Ontario Street and turns east along Elizabeth Street to connect to the ferry docks; the loop tour continues north out of town on county roads. The highway uses the ferry, run by the regional public transportation agency, to cross the De Tour Passage. Once on Drummond Island, M-134 follows Channel Road northward along the passage before turning eastward. The trunkline cuts across to run along Sturgeon Bay on the north shore of the island. On the east side of the bay, M-134 turns inland and runs east to the Four Corners, south of the unincorporated community of Drummond. The trunkline terminates at that intersection south of the [[Drummond Island Airport]] where Channel, Townline, Johnswood, and Shore roads (west, north, east and south respectively) come together.<ref name=MDOT10/><ref name=google/> M-134 is one of three state highways in Michigan located on an island; the two other state highways located on islands are M-185 on Mackinac Island and M-154 on Harsens Island.<ref name=MDOT10I>{{cite MDOT map |year=2010 |sections=D10, L14}}</ref>\n\nNo part of M-134 is listed on the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]],<ref name=NHS-MI>{{cite map|author=Michigan Department of Transportation |location=Lansing |scale=Scale not given |title=National Highway System, Michigan |date=April 23, 2006 |publisher=Michigan Department of Transportation |url=http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Statewide_150626_7.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=October 7, 2008 |url-status = dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004040152/http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Statewide_150626_7.pdf |archivedate=October 4, 2012 |df= }}</ref> a system of roadways important to the country's economy, defense, and mobility.<ref name=NHS>{{cite web |first1= Stefan |last1= Natzke |first2= Mike |last2= Neathery |first3= Kevin |last3= Adderly |url= http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/ |title= What is the National Highway System? |work= National Highway System |publisher= [[Federal Highway Administration]] |date= June 20, 2012 |accessdate= July 1, 2012 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> In 2009, the [[Michigan Department of Transportation]] (MDOT) conducted a survey to determine the traffic volume along the highway, reported using a metric called [[average annual daily traffic]] (AADT). The department determined that the highest count was the 3,595&nbsp;vehicles a day that used the highway west of the M-129 junction in Cedarville; the lowest counts were 608&nbsp;vehicles daily between the M-48 junction and the De Tour village limits. On the island, 667&nbsp;vehicles use M-134 daily.<ref name=TMIS>{{cite web |author= Bureau of Transportation Planning |url=http://mdotnetpublic.state.mi.us/tmispublic/ |title= Traffic Monitoring Information System |publisher=Michigan Department of Transportation |year=2008 |accessdate=May 10, 2011}}</ref> According to tourism officials in the area, over 100,000&nbsp;vehicles per year are transported round trip on the ferry with almost twice as many additional passengers.<ref name=ferry/>\n\n==Ferry==\n[[File:Drummond Island Ferry.jpg|thumb|300px|The SS ''Drummond Islander IV'' crossing the De Tour Passage near the MV ''American Mariner'']]\nThe Eastern Upper Peninsula Transportation Authority (EUPTA) operates the Drummond Island Ferry across the De Tour Passage in addition to two other ferries and the regional rural bus system for [[Luce County, Michigan|Luce]] and Chippewa counties.<ref name=eupta>{{cite web |url=http://www.eupta.net/ |title=Index |publisher= Eastern Upper Transportation Authority |author=Staff |date= March 11, 2011 |accessdate= May 10, 2011}}</ref> As part of the service between De Tour and Drummond Island, EUPTA operates up to three different vessels: the SS ''Drummond Islander'', SS ''Drummond Islander III'' and the SS ''Drummond Islander IV''. {{As of|2011}}, fares start at $12 per car and increase based on the size of the vehicle transported, including a [[fuel surcharge]]. Passenger fares are $2 for adults and $1 for seniors or students; the vehicle driver's fare is included in the vehicle charge. Ferries leave Drummond Island at 10 minutes after the hour, from De Tour at 20 minutes to the hour, and run most of the day; some crossing times are only operated seasonally.<ref name=ferry>{{cite web |url= http://www.drummondislandchamber.com/index.php?page=Transportation |title= Drummond Island Transportation: Ferry and Airport |publisher= Drummond Island Tourism Association |year= 2011 |author= Staff |accessdate= May 10, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110616051901/http://www.drummondislandchamber.com/index.php?page=Transportation |archive-date= June 16, 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> M-134 is one of two highways in Michigan to use a ferry connection; the other is US&nbsp;10 between Ludington, Michigan, and Manitowoc, Wisconsin.<ref name=MDOT10F>{{cite MDOT map |year= 2010 |sections=I5\u2013I7}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nStarting in late 1928 or early 1929, the first route designated as M-134 was a road in [[Missaukee County, Michigan|Missaukee County]] from [[M-66 (Michigan highway)|M-66]] three miles (4.8&nbsp;km) north of [[McBain, Michigan|McBain]] east to [[Falmouth, Michigan|Falmouth]] in the [[Northern Michigan|northern Lower Peninsula]].<ref name=MSHD28-10>{{cite MDOT map |date=1928-10-01 }}</ref><ref name=MSHD29-05>{{cite MDOT map |date=1929-05-01 }}</ref> In 1938, the [[Michigan State Highway Department]] (MSHD) returned the road to local control.<ref name=MSHD38-05>{{cite MDOT map |date=1938-05-01 |section=H10}}</ref><ref name=MSHD38-12>{{cite MDOT map |date=1938-12-01 |section=H10}}</ref>\n\nWhen the rest of the state highway system was first designated,<ref name=press-1919-09-20>{{cite news |title=Michigan May Do Well Following Wisconsin's Road Marking System |work=[[The Grand Rapids Press]] |date= September 20, 1919 |page=10}}</ref> by July 1, 1919, the first state highway in the area of today's M-134 was a section of [[M-12 (Michigan highway)|M-12]].<ref name=MSHD19UP>{{cite MDOT map |date= 1919-07-01U }}</ref> That highway segment was used for [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]] in 1926.<ref name=MSHD26-12>{{cite MDOT map |date=1926-12-01 }}</ref> A rerouting of US&nbsp;2 was completed in 1933 between [[Rogers Park, Michigan|Rogers Park]] and [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]]. The new routing followed [[Mackinac Trail]] instead of turning east to [[Cedarville, Michigan|Cedarville]] and north to Sault Ste. Marie. The former routing was given the [[M-121 (Michigan highway)|M-121]] designation,<ref name=MSHD33-05>{{cite MDOT map |date=1933-05-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref><ref name=MSHD33-09>{{cite MDOT map |date=1933-09-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref> and later M-4.<ref name=MSHD36-06>{{cite MDOT map |date=1936-06-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref>\n\nThe current designation appeared in the Upper Peninsula in 1939, soon after being removed from Missaukee County. It replaced the former M-4 route designation. At the time, M-134 was routed farther inland between US&nbsp;2 and a point north of Hessel. The highway ended at the Mackinac\u2013Chippewa county line, but an extension farther east was shown on maps of the time as under construction.<ref name=MSHD39-04>{{cite MDOT map |date=1939-04-15 |link= yes |c-link= yes |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref><ref name=MSHD39-12>{{cite MDOT map |date=1939-12-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref> This segment of roadway was completed in the latter half of 1940, extending M-134 to terminate at M-48 about {{convert|10|mi}} west of DeTour.<ref name=MSHD40-07>{{cite MDOT map |date=1940-07-15 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref><ref name=MSHD40-12>{{cite MDOT map |date=1940-12-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref> In 1950, a new roadway section was added to the state highway system, bypassing the former routing of M-48 west of DeTour; in the process the MSHD extended M-134 on this new highway and truncated M-48 to the junction south of [[Goetzville, Michigan|Goetzville]].<ref name=MSHD50-04>{{cite MDOT map |date=1950-04-15 |sections=D11\u2013D12}}</ref><ref name=MSHD50-07>{{cite MDOT map |date=1950-07-01 |sections=D11\u2013D12}}</ref>\n\nIn 1958, the highway west of Hessel was shifted to follow an alignment closer to Lake Huron; the MSHD transferred the former routing of M-134 to local control at that time.<ref name=MSHD57-10>{{cite MDOT map |date=1957-10-01 |sections=D10\u2013D11}}</ref><ref name=MSHD58>{{cite MDOT map |year=1958 |sections= D10\u2013D11}}</ref> In October 1963, the final section of I-75/US&nbsp;2 freeway opened in the UP;<ref name=AP>{{cite news |title= Walking Grandfather Completes Long Hike |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=f1MvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IKsFAAAAIBAJ&pg=879,5833952&dq=interstate+75+freeway&hl=en |work=[[Argus-Press]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |location=Owosso, MI |date=October 31, 1963 |page=14 |accessdate= May 10, 2011 |via= [[Google News]] }}</ref> M-134's western terminus was truncated slightly to end at the new freeway instead of the former routing of US&nbsp;2 along [[Mackinac Trail]].<ref name=MSHD63>{{cite MDOT map |year=1963 |section=D10}}</ref><ref name=MSHD64>{{cite MDOT map |year=1964 |section=D10}}</ref> In 1989, MDOT extended the trunkline to add a segment on Drummond Island; in the process, the Drummond Island Ferry across the DeTour Passage was added to the route.<ref name=MDOT89>{{cite MDOT map |year=1989 |section=D12}}</ref><ref name=MDOT90>{{cite MDOT map |year=1990 |section=D12}}</ref> The entire length of the highway was dedicated as a [[Pure Michigan Byway]] on October 16, 2015.<ref name=M-134-FreePress>{{cite news |date= October 14, 2015 |title= M-134 in UP Tapped as Pure Michigan's First Byway |url= http://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2015/10/14/pure-michigan-first-byway-highway-134/73921032/ |work= [[Detroit Free Press]] |agency= [[Associated Press]] |access-date= October 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{MIinttop|ref=<ref name=PRFA>{{cite MDOT PRFA |link= yes |accessdate= May 10, 2011}}</ref><ref name=CGI>{{cite web |author= Michigan Center for Geographic Information |title= Geographic Data Library |date=May 2007 |publisher= [[Michigan Department of Information Technology]] |url= http://www.mcgi.state.mi.us/mgdl/?rel=thext&action=thmname&cid=14&cat=MI+Geographic+Framework+All+Roads+%28v7b%29| accessdate=May 11, 2011 }}</ref>}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Mackinac\n|cspan=2\n|location=St. Ignace Township\n|mile=0.000\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MI|I|75|Tour|LHCT|dir2=south|city1=St. Ignace|city2=Sault Ste. Marie}}\n|notes=Exit&nbsp;359 on I-75; western end of LHCT concurrency}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Cedarville\n|mile=17.007\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|129|city1=Pickford|city2=Sault Ste. Marie|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of M-129}}\n{{jctco|state=MI|county=Chippewa}}\n{{jctco|state=MI|county=Mackinac}}\n{{MIint\n|county=Chippewa\n|cspan=3\n|location=DeTour Township\n|type=concur\n|mile=31.139\n|road={{jct|state=MI|M|48|Tour|LHCT|dir1=west|dir2=north|city1=Pickford}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of M-48; eastern end of LHCT concurrency mainline, spur route continues eastward}}\n{{jctbridge\n|location_special=[[DeTour Passage]]\n|mile=41.338\n|mile2=42.324\n|type=toll\n|bridge=[[File:Ferry Sign.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] Drummond Island Ferry (tolled)}}\n{{MIint\n|location=Drummond Township\n|mile=50.233\n|road=Four Corners\n|notes=}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur,toll}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Michigan Highways}}\n*[[SS Badger|SS ''Badger]], connects US&nbsp;10 across Lake Michigan\n*''[[Lake Express]]'', a modern ferry that follows a previous route that connected [[U.S. Route 16 in Michigan|US&nbsp;16]] across Lake Michigan\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n*[http://www.michiganhighways.org/listings/M-134.html M-134] at Michigan Highways\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M134}}\n[[Category:State highways in Michigan|134]]\n[[Category:Lake Huron Circle Tour]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Mackinac County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Chippewa County, Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Imzadi1979", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:tweak", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M-134_(Michigan_highway)"}
{"title_page": "USS Everett (PF-8)", "text_new": "{{short description|Tacoma-class patrol frigate}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= USS Everett 120800801.jpg\n|Ship caption= USS ''Everett'' (PF-8)\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1945}}\n|Ship name=''Everett''\n|Ship namesake=City of [[Everett, Washington|Everett]], Washington\n|Ship reclassified=Patrol Frigate (PF), 15 April 1943\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=yes\n|Ship ordered= as a [[Patrol frigate|Type S2-S2-AQ1]] hull, [[Maritime Commission|MCE]] hull 1426{{sfn|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n|Ship builder=[[Permanente Metals]] [[Richmond Shipyards|Richmond Shipyard #4]], [[Richmond, California|Richmond]], California\n|Ship yard number= 51{{sfn|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n|Ship laid down=31 July 1943\n|Ship launched= 29 September 1943 \n|Ship sponsor= Mrs. Cornelia M. Fitch\n|Ship commissioned= 22 January 1944 \n|Ship decommissioned= 16 August 1945\n|Ship struck=  1 December 1961\n|Ship identification=*[[Hull classification symbol#Patrol combatant type|Hull symbol]]: PG-116\n*Hull symbol: PF-8\n*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: NGBY\n*{{ICS|November}}{{ICS|Golf}}{{ICS|Bravo}}{{ICS|Yankee}}\n|Ship fate=Transferred to [[Soviet Navy]] 16 August 1945{{efn|name=fn1}}\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Soviet Union\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Soviet Union|naval-1935}}\n|Ship name= ''EK-15''{{efn|name=fn2}}\n|Ship acquired=16 August 1945\n|Ship commissioned=16 August 1945{{efn|name=fn3}}\n|Ship decommissioned=16 October 1949\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship fate= Returned to United States, 16 October 1949\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1953}}\n|Ship name=''Albuquerque''\n|Ship acquired=16 October 1949\n|Ship recommissioned=26 July 1950\n|Ship decommissioned=10 May 1953\n|Ship honors=[[Image:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|18px]] 4 \u00d7 [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle stars]] for [[Korean War]] service\n|Ship fate=Transferred to [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]], 30 November 1953\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Japan\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Japan|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Kiri''\n|Ship acquired= March 1953\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned= 1 October 1975\n|Ship renamed=''YAC-20'', 31 March 1970\n|Ship reclassified= Auxiliary stock craft (YAC), 31 March 1970\n|Ship identification=  Hull symbol: PF-291/YAC-20\n|Ship fate=Returned to United States, 22 January 1976\n|Ship status=Scrapped\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption={{sfn|Navsource}}\n|Ship class= {{sclass-|Tacoma|frigate|2}} [[patrol frigate]]\n|Ship displacement={{Tacoma class frigate displacement}}\n|Ship length= {{Tacoma class frigate length}}\n|Ship beam= {{Tacoma class frigate beam}}\n|Ship draft= {{Tacoma class frigate draft}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship power= {{Tacoma class frigate power}}\n|Ship propulsion={{Tacoma class frigate propulsion}}\n|Ship speed= {{Tacoma class frigate speed}}\n|Ship range= \n|Ship complement=190\n|Ship armament={{Tacoma class frigate armament}}\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USS ''Everett'' (PG-116/PF-8)''', a {{sclass-|Tacoma|frigate|0}} [[patrol frigate]] in commission from 1944 to 1945 and from 1950 to 1953, thus far has been the only ship of the [[United States Navy]] to be named for [[Everett, Washington|Everett]], Washington. She also served in the [[Soviet Navy]] as '''''EK-15''''' and in the [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] as '''JDS ''Kiri'' (PF-11/PF-291/YAC-20)'''.\n\n==Construction and commissioning==\nOriginally classified as a [[gunboat|patrol gunboat]], '''PG-116''', ''Everett'' was reclassified as a [[patrol frigate]], '''PF-8''', on 15 April 1943. She was [[Keel laying|laid down]] under a [[Maritime Commission]] (MARCOM) contract, MC hull 1426, at the [[Permanente Metals]] [[Richmond Shipyards|Richmond Shipyard #4]], [[Richmond, California|Richmond]], California.{{sfn|Navsource}} ''Everett'' was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 29 September 1943, sponsored by Mrs. Cornelia M. Fitch, and was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 22 January 1944, with [[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] W. L. Davis, [[USCG]], in command.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n==Service history==\n\n===U.S. Navy, World War II, 1944\u20131945===\nAfter [[Shakedown (testing)|shakedown]] and training, ''Everett'' steamed north to [[Adak, Alaska|Adak]], [[Territory of Alaska]], arriving there on 22 April 1944, and began 16 months of [[patrol]] and escort duty in the [[Aleutian Islands]].{{sfn|DANFS|2015}} Selected for transfer to the [[Soviet Navy]] in [[Project Hula]] &ndash; a secret program for the transfer of U.S. Navy ships to the Soviet Navy at [[Cold Bay, Alaska|Cold Bay]], Alaska, in anticipation of the [[Soviet Union]] joining the [[Pacific War|war against Japan]] &ndash; she then proceeded to Cold Bay in the summer of 1945 and began training her new Soviet crew.{{sfn|Russell|1997|p=39}}\n\n===Soviet Navy, 1945\u20131949===\n\nFollowing the completion of training for her Soviet crew, ''Everett'' was [[Ship decommissioning|decommissioned]] on 16 August 1945 at Cold Bay and transferred to the Soviet Union under [[Lend-Lease]] immediately{{efn|name=fn1}} along with her [[sister ship]]s {{USS|Tacoma|PF-3|3}}, {{USS|Sausalito|PF-4|3}}, {{USS|Hoquiam|PF-5|3}}, {{USS|Pasco|PF-6|3}}, and {{USS|Albuquerque|PF-7|3}}. Commissioned into the Soviet Navy immediately,{{efn|name=fn3}} ''Everett'' was designated as a ''storozhevoi korabl'' (\"escort ship\") and renamed '''''EK-15'''''{{efn|name=fn2}} in Soviet service. She soon departed Cold Bay bound for [[Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky]] in the Soviet Union, where she served as a patrol vessel in the [[Soviet Far East]].{{sfn|Russell|1997|p=39}}\n\nIn February 1946, the United States began negotiations for the return of ships loaned to the Soviet Union for use during World War II. On 8 May 1947, [[United States Secretary of the Navy]] [[James V. Forrestal]] informed the [[United States Department of State]] that the [[United States Department of the Navy]] wanted 480 of the 585 combatant ships it had transferred to the Soviet Union for World War II use returned, ''EK-15'' among them. Negotiations for the return of the ships were protracted, but on 15 November 1949 the Soviet Union finally returned ''EK-15'' to the U.S. Navy at [[United States Fleet Activities Yokosuka|Yokosuka]], [[Japan]].{{sfn|Russell|1997|pp=37-39}}\n\n===U.S. Navy, Korean War, 1950\u20131953===\nReverting to her original name, ''Everett'' was given an extensive [[wikt:overhaul|overhaul]] at Yokosuka, where she was recommissioned on 26 July 1950, for service during the [[Korean War]]. Assigned to primary duty as [[station ship]] at [[Hong Kong]], she also joined the [[United Nations]] Blockading and Escort Force in operations off both coasts of [[Korea]]. On 3 July 1951, while [[Blockad of Wonsan|bombarding Wonsan]], North Korea, ''Everett'' was hit by fire from a [[shore battery]]; one man was killed and seven were wounded, but damage to the ship was light.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n===Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force, 1953\u20131976===\n\n{{Other ships|Japanese ship Kiri}}\n\nOn 10 March 1953, ''Everett'' was decommissioned at Yokosuka and lent to [[Japan]], entering service with the [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] as {{nihongo|'''JDS ''Kiri'' (PF-11)'''|\u304d\u308a (PF-11)||\"[[Paulownia tomentosa|paulownia]]\"}}.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} ''Kiri'' was redesignated '''PF-291''' on 1 September 1957.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} The United States struck her from the [[Navy List]] on 1 December 1961. She was reclassified as an \"auxiliary stock craft\" (YAC) and renamed '''''YAC-20''''' on 31 March 1970.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} Decommissioned on 1 October 1975, she was returned to the United States on 22 January 1976 for disposal and subsequently scrapped.{{sfn|Navsource}}\n\n==Awards==\nThe US Navy awarded ''Everett'' four [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle stars]] for her Korean War service.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|refs=\n{{efn|name=fn1|[http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/08008.htm NavSource Online: Frigate Photo Archive Everett (PF 8) ex-PG-116] states that ''Everett'' was transferred to the Soviet Navy on 17 August 1945, but the [http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/e5/everett.htm ''Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships'' ''Everett''] article states that ''Everett'' was transferred on 16 August 1945 and [http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/pf8.htm hazegray.org ''Everett''] repeats this. Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, p. 39, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], also reports that the transfer date was 16 August 1945. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n{{efn|name=fn2|[http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/080008.htm NavSource Online: Frigate Photo Archive Everett (PF 8) ex-PG-116] states that ''Everett'' was named ''EK-17'' in Soviet service, but Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, p. 39, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], reports that the ship's Soviet name was ''EK-15''. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n{{efn|name=fn3|According to Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], Project Hula ships were commissioned into the Soviet Navy simultaneously with their transfer from the U.S. Navy &ndash; see photo captions on p. 24 regarding the transfers of various [[large infantry landing craft]] (LCI(L)s) and information on p. 27 about the transfer of {{USS|Coronado|PF-38}}, which Russell says typified the transfer process. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite DANFS \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | url = https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/e/everett.html \n  | title = Everett (PF-8)\n  | publisher = Naval History and Heritage Command \n  | date = 8 June 2015\n  | accessdate = 13 November 2018\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|DANFS|2015}}\n  }}{{PD-notice}}\n* {{cite web\n  | url = http://shipbuildinghistory.com/shipyards/emergencylarge/krichmond.htm\n  | title = Kaiser Permanente No. 4, Richmond CA\n  | publisher =  www.ShipbuildingHistory.com\n  | date = 5 February 2014\n  | accessdate = 9 November 2018\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n  }}\n* {{cite web \n  | url = http://www