untry=Japan\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Japan|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Kiri''\n|Ship acquired= March 1953\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned= 1 October 1975\n|Ship renamed=''YAC-20'', 31 March 1970\n|Ship reclassified= Auxiliary stock craft (YAC), 31 March 1970\n|Ship identification=  Hull symbol: PF-291/YAC-20\n|Ship fate=Returned to United States, 22 January 1976\n|Ship status=Scrapped\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption={{sfn|Navsource}}\n|Ship class= {{sclass-|Tacoma|frigate|2}} [[patrol frigate]]\n|Ship displacement={{Tacoma class frigate displacement}}\n|Ship length= {{Tacoma class frigate length}}\n|Ship beam= {{Tacoma class frigate beam}}\n|Ship draft= {{Tacoma class frigate draft}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship power= {{Tacoma class frigate power}}\n|Ship propulsion={{Tacoma class frigate propulsion}}\n|Ship speed= {{Tacoma class frigate speed}}\n|Ship range= \n|Ship complement=190\n|Ship armament={{Tacoma class frigate armament}}\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USS ''Everett'' (PG-116/PF-8)''', a {{sclass-|Tacoma|frigate|0}} [[patrol frigate]] in commission from 1944 to 1945 and from 1950 to 1953, thus far has been the only ship of the [[United States Navy]] to be named for [[Everett, Washington|Everett]], Washington. She also served in the [[Soviet Navy]] as '''''EK-15''''' and in the [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] as '''JDS ''Kiri'' (PF-11/PF-291/YAC-20)'''.\n\n==Construction and commissioning==\nOriginally classified as a patrol [[gunboat|patrol gunboat]], '''PG-116''', ''Everett'' was reclassified as a [[patrol frigate]], '''PF-8''', on 15 April 1943. She was [[Keel laying|laid down]] under a [[Maritime Commission]] (MARCOM) contract, MC hull 1426, at the [[Permanente Metals]] [[Richmond Shipyards|Richmond Shipyard #4]], [[Richmond, California|Richmond]], California.{{sfn|Navsource}} ''Everett'' was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 29 September 1943, sponsored by Mrs. Cornelia M. Fitch, and was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 22 January 1944, with [[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] W. L. Davis, [[USCG]], in command.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n==Service history==\n\n===U.S. Navy, World War II, 1944\u20131945===\nAfter [[Shakedown (testing)|shakedown]] and training, ''Everett'' steamed north to [[Adak, Alaska|Adak]], [[Territory of Alaska]], arriving there on 22 April 1944, and began 16 months of [[patrol]] and escort duty in the [[Aleutian Islands]].{{sfn|DANFS|2015}} Selected for transfer to the [[Soviet Navy]] in [[Project Hula]] &ndash; a secret program for the transfer of U.S. Navy ships to the Soviet Navy at [[Cold Bay, Alaska|Cold Bay]], Alaska, in anticipation of the [[Soviet Union]] joining the [[Pacific War|war against Japan]] &ndash; she then proceeded to Cold Bay in the summer of 1945 and began training her new Soviet crew.{{sfn|Russell|1997|p=39}}\n\n===Soviet Navy, 1945\u20131949===\n\nFollowing the completion of training for her Soviet crew, ''Everett'' was [[Ship decommissioning|decommissioned]] on 16 August 1945 at Cold Bay and transferred to the Soviet Union under [[Lend-Lease]] immediately{{efn|name=fn1}} along with her [[sister ship]]s {{USS|Tacoma|PF-3|3}}, {{USS|Sausalito|PF-4|3}}, {{USS|Hoquiam|PF-5|3}}, {{USS|Pasco|PF-6|3}}, and {{USS|Albuquerque|PF-7|3}}. Commissioned into the Soviet Navy immediately,{{efn|name=fn3}} ''Everett'' was designated as a ''storozhevoi korabl'' (\"escort ship\") and renamed '''''EK-15'''''{{efn|name=fn2}} in Soviet service. She soon departed Cold Bay bound for [[Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky]] in the Soviet Union, where she served as a patrol vessel in the [[Soviet Far East]].{{sfn|Russell|1997|p=39}}\n\nIn February 1946, the United States began negotiations for the return of ships loaned to the Soviet Union for use during World War II. On 8 May 1947, [[United States Secretary of the Navy]] [[James V. Forrestal]] informed the [[United States Department of State]] that the [[United States Department of the Navy]] wanted 480 of the 585 combatant ships it had transferred to the Soviet Union for World War II use returned, ''EK-15'' among them. Negotiations for the return of the ships were protracted, but on 15 November 1949 the Soviet Union finally returned ''EK-15'' to the U.S. Navy at [[United States Fleet Activities Yokosuka|Yokosuka]], [[Japan]].{{sfn|Russell|1997|pp=37-39}}\n\n===U.S. Navy, Korean War, 1950\u20131953===\nReverting to her original name, ''Everett'' was given an extensive [[wikt:overhaul|overhaul]] at Yokosuka, where she was recommissioned on 26 July 1950, for service during the [[Korean War]]. Assigned to primary duty as [[station ship]] at [[Hong Kong]], she also joined the [[United Nations]] Blockading and Escort Force in operations off both coasts of [[Korea]]. On 3 July 1951, while [[Blockad of Wonsan|bombarding Wonsan]], North Korea, ''Everett'' was hit by fire from a [[shore battery]]; one man was killed and seven were wounded, but damage to the ship was light.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n===Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force, 1953\u20131976===\n\n{{Other ships|Japanese ship Kiri}}\n\nOn 10 March 1953, ''Everett'' was decommissioned at Yokosuka and lent to [[Japan]], entering service with the [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] as {{nihongo|'''JDS ''Kiri'' (PF-11)'''|\u304d\u308a (PF-11)||\"[[Paulownia tomentosa|paulownia]]\"}}.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} ''Kiri'' was redesignated '''PF-291''' on 1 September 1957.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} The United States struck her from the [[Navy List]] on 1 December 1961. She was reclassified as an \"auxiliary stock craft\" (YAC) and renamed '''''YAC-20''''' on 31 March 1970.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} Decommissioned on 1 October 1975, she was returned to the United States on 22 January 1976 for disposal and subsequently scrapped.{{sfn|Navsource}}\n\n==Awards==\nThe US Navy awarded ''Everett'' four [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle stars]] for her Korean War service.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|refs=\n{{efn|name=fn1|[http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/08008.htm NavSource Online: Frigate Photo Archive Everett (PF 8) ex-PG-116] states that ''Everett'' was transferred to the Soviet Navy on 17 August 1945, but the [http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/e5/everett.htm ''Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships'' ''Everett''] article states that ''Everett'' was transferred on 16 August 1945 and [http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/pf8.htm hazegray.org ''Everett''] repeats this. Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, p. 39, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], also reports that the transfer date was 16 August 1945. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n{{efn|name=fn2|[http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/080008.htm NavSource Online: Frigate Photo Archive Everett (PF 8) ex-PG-116] states that ''Everett'' was named ''EK-17'' in Soviet service, but Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, p. 39, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], reports that the ship's Soviet name was ''EK-15''. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n{{efn|name=fn3|According to Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], Project Hula ships were commissioned into the Soviet Navy simultaneously with their transfer from the U.S. Navy &ndash; see photo captions on p. 24 regarding the transfers of various [[large infantry landing craft]] (LCI(L)s) and information on p. 27 about the transfer of {{USS|Coronado|PF-38}}, which Russell says typified the transfer process. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite DANFS \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | url = https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/e/everett.html \n  | title = Everett (PF-8)\n  | publisher = Naval History and Heritage Command \n  | date = 8 June 2015\n  | accessdate = 13 November 2018\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|DANFS|2015}}\n  }}{{PD-notice}}\n* {{cite web\n  | url = http://shipbuildinghistory.com/shipyards/emergencylarge/krichmond.htm\n  | title = Kaiser Permanente No. 4, Richmond CA\n  | publisher =  www.ShipbuildingHistory.com\n  | date = 5 February 2014\n  | accessdate = 9 November 2018\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n  }}\n* {{cite web \n  | url = http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/08008.htm \n  | title= Everett (PF 8)\n  | publisher= Navsource.org \n  | date= \n  | accessdate= 13 November 2018\n  | ref= {{sfnRef|Navsource}}\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  |last= Russell\n  |first= Richard A.\n  |title= Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan\n  |location= Washington, D.C.\n  |publisher= [[Naval Historical Center]]\n  |date= 1997\n  |ref= harv\n  |isbn= 0-945274-35-1\n  }}\n* {{cite web \n  |title = The Naval Database: JMSDF Kusu class patrol frigate (PF291) Kiri \n  |url = http://hush.gooside.com/name/k/Ki/Kiri/Kiri.html#anchor110419 \n  |language=Japanese \n  |ref = {{SfnRef|The Naval Database}} \n  |accessdate = 2014-09-22\n  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{navsource|12/08008|USS Everett}}\n*[http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/pf8.htm hazegray.org: USS ''Everett'']\n*\n\n <!-- non-breaking space to keep AWB drones from altering the space before the navbox-->\n\n{{Tacoma class frigate|others}}\n{{Kaiser, Richmond Ship Yards}}\n{{Project Hula ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Everett (PF-8)}}\n[[Category:Tacoma-class frigates]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Richmond, California]]\n[[Category:1943 ships]]\n[[Category:World War II frigates and destroyer escorts of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Navy Washington (state)-related ships]]\n[[Category:Everett, Washington]]\n[[Category:Tacoma-class frigates of the Soviet Navy]]\n[[Category:World War II frigates of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Cold War frigates of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Cold War frigates and destroyer escorts of the United States]]\n[[Category:Korean War frigates and destroyer escorts of the United States]]\n[[Category:Tacoma-class frigates of the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]]\n[[Category:Ships transferred under Project Hula]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eConstruction and commissioning:Typo fixing, replaced: patrolpatrol gunboat\u2192patrol gunboat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USS_Everett_(PF-8)"}
{"title_page": "USS Albuquerque (PF-7)", "text_new": "{{short description|Tacoma-class patrol frigate}}\n{{other ships|USS Albuquerque}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Uss Albuquerque 120800703.jpg\n|image alt=\n|Ship caption=USS ''Albuquerque'' (PF-7)\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1953}}\n|Ship name=''Albuquerque''\n|Ship namesake=City of [[Albuquerque]], New Mexico\n|Ship reclassified=Patrol Frigate (PF), 15 April 1943\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=yes\n|Ship ordered= as a [[Patrol frigate|Type S2-S2-AQ1]] hull, [[Maritime Commission|MCE]] hull 1425{{sfn|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n|Ship builder=[[Permanente Metals]] [[Richmond Shipyards|Richmond Shipyard #4]], [[Richmond, California|Richmond]], California\n|Ship yard number= 50{{sfn|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n|Ship laid down=20 July 1943\n|Ship launched=14 September 1943\n|Ship sponsor= Mrs. B. L. Livingstone\n|Ship commissioned=20 December 1943\n|Ship decommissioned=16 August 1945\n|Ship struck=1 December 1961\n|Ship identification=*[[Hull classification symbol#Patrol combatant type|Hull symbol]]: PG-115\n*Hull symbol: PF-7\n*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: NFFG\n*{{ICS|November}}{{ICS|Foxtrot}}{{ICS|Foxtrot}}{{ICS|Golf}}\n|Ship fate=Transferred to [[Soviet Navy]] 16 August 1945{{efn|name=fn1}}\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Soviet Union\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Soviet Union|naval-1935}}\n|Ship name= ''EK-14''{{efn|name=fn2}}\n|Ship acquired=16 August 1945\n|Ship commissioned=16 August 1945{{efn|name=fn3}}\n|Ship decommissioned=16 October 1949\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship fate= returned to United States, 16 October 1949\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1951}}\n|Ship name=''Albuquerque''\n|Ship acquired=16 October 1949\n|Ship recommissioned=3 October 1950\n|Ship decommissioned=28 February 1953\n|Ship honors=[[Image:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|18px]] 3 \u00d7 [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle stars]] for [[Korean War]] service\n|Ship fate=Transferred to [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]], 30 November 1953\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Japan\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Japan|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Tochi''\n|Ship acquired=30 November 1953\n|Ship commissioned= 31 March 1969\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=yes\n|Ship renamed=''YAC-15'', 31 March 1965\n|Ship reclassified=Auxiliary stock craft (YAC), 31 March 1965\n|Ship identification=  Hull symbol: PF-296/YAC-15\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship fate=Returned to United States, 9 July 1971\n|Ship status=Unknown\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption={{sfn|Navsource}}\n|Ship class= {{sclass-|Tacoma|frigate|2}} [[patrol frigate]]\n|Ship displacement={{Tacoma class frigate displacement}}\n|Ship length= {{Tacoma class frigate length}}\n|Ship beam= {{Tacoma class frigate beam}}\n|Ship draft= {{Tacoma class frigate draft}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship power= {{Tacoma class frigate power}}\n|Ship propulsion={{Tacoma class frigate propulsion}}\n|Ship speed= {{Tacoma class frigate speed}}\n|Ship range= \n|Ship complement=190\n|Ship armament={{Tacoma class frigate armament}}\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USS ''Albuquerque'' (PG-115/PF-7)''', a {{sclass-|Tacoma|frigate|0}} [[patrol frigate]] in commission from 1943 to 1945 and from 1950 to 1953, was the first ship of the [[United States Navy]] to be named for [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]. She also served in the [[Soviet Navy]] as '''''EK-14''''' and in the [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] as '''JDS ''Tochi'' (PF-16/PF-296)''' and as '''''YAC-15'''''.\n\n==Construction and commissioning==\n''Albuquerque'', originally classified as a [[gunboat|patrol gunboat]], '''PG-115''', but reclassified as a patrol frigate, '''PF-7''', on 15 April 1943, was [[Keel laying|laid down]] under a [[Maritime Commission]] (MARCOM) contract, MC hull 1425, on 20 July 1943, at the [[Permanente Metals]] [[Richmond Shipyards|Richmond Shipyard #4]], [[Richmond, California|Richmond]], California. [[Ship naming and launching|Launched]] on 14 September 1943, sponsored by Mrs. B. L. Livingstone, the ship was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 20 December 1943, with [[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] Wayne L. Goff, [[USCG]], in command.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n==Service history==\n\n===U.S. Navy, World War II, 1943&ndash;1945===\nAfter [[Fitting-out|fitting out]] and [[Shakedown (testing)|shakedown]] training, ''Albuquerque'' stood out from [[Treasure Island, California|Treasure Island]], California, on 24 March 1944, bound for [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]], Washington. She arrived at Seattle, on 26 March 1944, and remained there until getting underway on 5 April 1944, as an escort for a [[convoy]] bound for the [[Territory of Alaska]]. She and her convoy arrived at [[Dutch Harbor, Alaska|Dutch Harbor]], on [[Unalaska Island]], in the [[Aleutian Islands]], on 16 April 1944, where she  was assigned to [[Escort Division 27]]. After the [[Liberty ship]] {{SS|John Straub||2}}, operating as a [[cargo ship]] for the [[United States Army]], either struck a [[naval mine|mine]] or was [[torpedo]]ed by the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] [[submarine]] {{ship|Japanese submarine|I-180||2}} and broke in two in the [[Pacific Ocean]] at {{coord|54|22|N|163|24|W|name=SS ''John Straub''}}, approximately {{convert|20|nmi}} southeast of [[Sanak Island]] in the [[Fox Islands (Alaska)|Fox Islands]] subgroup of the [[Aleutian Islands]] on 19 April 1944 and her [[Bow (ship)|bow]] section sank, ''Albuquerque'' [[Scuttling|scuttled]] her [[stern]] section.<ref name=alaskashipwrecksj>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-j/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (J)]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsJo.html |title=Liberty Ships \u2013 Joaquin \u2013 Johns |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor the rest of 1944 and the first half of 1945, ''Albuquerque'' shepherded convoys between various Alaskan ports and conducted patrols around the Aleutian Islands and in the [[Bering Sea]].{{sfn|DANFS|2015}} Between 5 June and 14 July 1945, ''Albuquerque'' made a round-trip voyage from Dutch Harbor to Seattle and back. Selected for transfer to the [[Soviet Navy]] in [[Project Hula]] &ndash; a secret program for the transfer of U.S. Navy ships to the Soviet Navy at [[Cold Bay, Alaska|Cold Bay]], Alaska, in anticipation of the [[Soviet Union]] joining the [[Pacific War|war against Japan]] &ndash; she then proceeded to Cold Bay and began training her new Soviet crew.{{sfn|Russell|1997|p=39}}\n\n===Soviet Navy, 1945\u20131949===\n\nFollowing the completion of training for her Soviet crew, ''Albuquerque'' was [[Ship decommissioning|decommissioned]] on 16 August 1945, at Cold Bay, and transferred to the Soviet Union under [[Lend-Lease]] immediately along with her [[sister ship]]s {{USS|Tacoma|PF-3|3}}, {{USS|Sausalito|PF-4|3}}, {{USS|Hoquiam|PF-5|3}}, {{USS|Pasco|PF-6|3}}, and {{USS|Everett|PF-8|3}}. Commissioned into the Soviet Navy immediately,{{efn|name=fn1}}{{efn|name=fn3}} ''Albuquerque'' was designated as a ''storozhevoi korabl'' (\"escort ship\") and renamed '''''EK-14'''''{{efn|name=fn2}} in Soviet service. She soon departed Cold Bay, bound for [[Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky]] in the Soviet Union, where she served as a patrol vessel in the [[Soviet Far East]].{{sfn|Russell|1997|p=39}}\n\nIn February 1946, the United States began negotiations for the return of ships loaned to the Soviet Union for use during World War II. On 8 May 1947, [[United States Secretary of the Navy]] [[James V. Forrestal]] informed the [[United States Department of State]] that the [[United States Department of the Navy]] wanted 480 of the 585 combatant ships it had transferred to the Soviet Union for World War II use returned, ''EK-14'' among them. Negotiations for the return of the ships were protracted, but on 15 November 1949, the Soviet Union finally returned ''EK-14'' to the US Navy at [[United States Fleet Activities Yokosuka|Yokosuka]], [[Japan]].{{sfn|Russell|1997|pp=37\u201339}}\n\n===U.S. Navy, Korean War, 1950&ndash;1953===\nReverting to her former name, ''Albuquerque'' lay idle in the [[Pacific Reserve Fleet]] at Yokosuka until the outbreak of the [[Korean War]], on 25 June 1950, created a demand for more US Navy escort ships. Following repairs and refurbishment, she was recommissioned at Yokosuka, on 3 October 1950, with Lieutenant Commander Claude O. Lowe in command. For the next 10 months, she escorted convoys and conducted patrols between Yokosuka, [[Hong Kong]], and [[Singapore]]. In August 1951, she operated between Yokosuka and [[Subic Bay]] on [[Luzon]] in the [[Philippine Islands]]. On 10 December 1951, she departed Yokosuka, stopped at [[United States Fleet Activities Sasebo|Sasebo]], Japan, and, on 15 September 1951, got underway from Sasebo for patrol and escort duty along the eastern coast of [[Korea]].  As a unit of [[Escort Division 5]], [[Destroyer]] [[Flotilla]] 3, [[United States Pacific Fleet]], she spent the rest of September 1951 and most of October 1951 operating along the Korean coast.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n''Albuquerque'' concluded that duty on 26 October 1951, when she departed Sasebo bound for Hong Kong. She arrived in at Hong Kong on 30 October 1951 and remained there, presumably in some sort of [[station ship]] status, until March 1952. On 6 March 1952, she stood out of Hong Kong, bound for Subic Bay in the Philippines. From Subic Bay, she headed back to Japan, returning to Sasebo on 16 May 1952. Based there, she resumed [[patrol]] and escort duties along the eastern coast of Korea. That assignment lasted for about six weeks. In July 1952, she again visited Subic Bay, and on 26 July 1952, arrived in Hong Kong. She once more made an extended visit to Hong Kong, until finally departing in mid-November 1952. After a visit to Subic Bay, she returned to Sasebo, on 3 December 1952, and resumed duty along the eastern coast of Korea. On 28 February 1953, she was decommissioned at Yokosuka.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n===Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force, 1953&ndash;1968===\n\n{{other ships|Japanese ship Tochi}}\n\nOn 30 November 1953, the United States loaned the ship to Japan, and she was commissioned in the [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] as {{Nihongo|'''JDS ''Tochi'' (PF-16)'''|\u3068\u3061 (PF-16)||\"[[aesculus turbinata]]\"}}.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} The JMSDF reclassified her as '''''PF-296''''' on 1 September 1957.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} The US Navy struck her from the [[Navy List]] on 1 December 1961, but she was returned briefly to US Navy custody on 28 August 1962, before the United States almost simultaneously transferred her back to Japan permanently. Reclassified as an \"auxiliary stock craft\" (YAC) and renamed '''''YAC-15''''' on 31 March 1965,{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} she was decommissioned on 31 March 1969, and returned to US custody on 9 July 1971, for disposal. Her final disposition is unknown.{{sfn|Navsource}}\n\n==Awards==\n\nThe US Navy awarded ''Albuquerque'' three [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle stars]] for her Korean War service.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|refs=\n{{efn|name=fn1|The [http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/a5/albuquerque-i.htm ''Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships'' ''Albuquerque'' I\"] article states that ''Albuquerque'' was transferred to the Soviet Navy on 17 August 1945, and [http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/08007.htm NavSource Online: Frigate Photo Archive Albuquerque (PF 7) ex-PG-115] and [http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/pf7.htm hazegray.org ''Albuquerque''] repeat this date, but more recent research in Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, p. 39, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], reports that the transfer date was 16 August 1945. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n{{efn|name=fn2|[http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/08007.htm NavSource Online: Frigate Photo Archive Albuquerque (PF 7) ex-PG-115] asserts that ''Albuquerque'' was named ''EK-16'' in Soviet Navy service without citing a source for this name, but Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, p. 39, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], reports that the ship's Soviet name was ''EK-14''. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n{{efn|name=fn3|According to Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], Project Hula ships were commissioned into the Soviet Navy simultaneously with their transfer from the U.S. Navy; see photo captions on p. 24 regarding the transfers of various [[large infantry landing craft]] (LCI(L)s) and information on p. 27 about the transfer of {{USS|Coronado|PF-38}}, which Russell says typified the transfer process. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite DANFS \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | url = https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/a/albuquerque-i.html \n  | title = Albuquerque I (PF-7)\n  | publisher = Naval History and Heritage Command \n  | date = 15 June 2015\n  | accessdate = 9 November 2018\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|DANFS|2015}}\n  }}{{PD-notice}}\n* {{cite web\n  | url = http://shipbuildinghistory.com/shipyards/emergencylarge/krichmond.htm\n  | title = Kaiser Permanente No. 4, Richmond CA\n  | publisher =  www.ShipbuildingHistory.com\n  | date = 5 February 2014\n  | accessdate = 9 November 2018\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n  }}\n* {{cite web \n  | url = http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/08007.htm \n  | title= Albuquerque (PF 7)\n  | publisher= Navsource.org \n  | date= \n  | accessdate= 9 November 2018\n  | ref= {{sfnRef|Navsource}}\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  |last= Russell\n  |first= Richard A.\n  |title= Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan\n  |location= Washington, D.C.\n  |publisher= [[Naval Historical Center]]\n  |date= 1997\n  |ref= harv\n  |isbn= 0-945274-35-1\n  }}\n* {{cite web\n  | title = The Naval Database: JMSDF Kusu class patrol frigate (PF296) Tochi \n  | url = http://hush.gooside.com/name/t/To/tochi.html#anchor7543 \n  | language=Japanese \n  | ref = {{SfnRef|The Naval Database}} \n  | accessdate = 2014-09-22 \n  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{navsource|12/08007|USS Albuquerque}}\n* [http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/pf7.htm hazegray.org: USS ''Albuquerque'']\n\n <!-- non-breaking space to keep AWB drones from altering the space before the navbox-->\n\n{{Tacoma class frigate|others}}\n{{Kaiser, Richmond Ship Yards}}\n{{Project Hula ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albuquerque (PF-7)}}\n[[Category:Tacoma-class frigates]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Richmond, California]]\n[[Category:1943 ships]]\n[[Category:World War II frigates and destroyer escorts of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Navy New Mexico-related ships]]\n[[Category:Tacoma-class frigates of the Soviet Navy]]\n[[Category:World War II frigates of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Cold War frigates of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Cold War frigates and destroyer escorts of the United States]]\n[[Category:Korean War frigates and destroyer escorts of the United States]]\n[[Category:Tacoma-class frigates of the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]]\n[[Category:Ships transferred under Project Hula]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tacoma-class patrol frigate}}\n{{other ships|USS Albuquerque}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Uss Albuquerque 120800703.jpg\n|image alt=\n|Ship caption=USS ''Albuquerque'' (PF-7)\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1953}}\n|Ship name=''Albuquerque''\n|Ship namesake=City of [[Albuquerque]], New Mexico\n|Ship reclassified=Patrol Frigate (PF), 15 April 1943\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=yes\n|Ship ordered= as a [[Patrol frigate|Type S2-S2-AQ1]] hull, [[Maritime Commission|MCE]] hull 1425{{sfn|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n|Ship builder=[[Permanente Metals]] [[Richmond Shipyards|Richmond Shipyard #4]], [[Richmond, California|Richmond]], California\n|Ship yard number= 50{{sfn|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n|Ship laid down=20 July 1943\n|Ship launched=14 September 1943\n|Ship sponsor= Mrs. B. L. Livingstone\n|Ship commissioned=20 December 1943\n|Ship decommissioned=16 August 1945\n|Ship struck=1 December 1961\n|Ship identification=*[[Hull classification symbol#Patrol combatant type|Hull symbol]]: PG-115\n*Hull symbol: PF-7\n*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: NFFG\n*{{ICS|November}}{{ICS|Foxtrot}}{{ICS|Foxtrot}}{{ICS|Golf}}\n|Ship fate=Transferred to [[Soviet Navy]] 16 August 1945{{efn|name=fn1}}\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Soviet Union\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Soviet Union|naval-1935}}\n|Ship name= ''EK-14''{{efn|name=fn2}}\n|Ship acquired=16 August 1945\n|Ship commissioned=16 August 1945{{efn|name=fn3}}\n|Ship decommissioned=16 October 1949\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship fate= returned to United States, 16 October 1949\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1951}}\n|Ship name=''Albuquerque''\n|Ship acquired=16 October 1949\n|Ship recommissioned=3 October 1950\n|Ship decommissioned=28 February 1953\n|Ship honors=[[Image:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|18px]] 3 \u00d7 [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle stars]] for [[Korean War]] service\n|Ship fate=Transferred to [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]], 30 November 1953\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Japan\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Japan|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Tochi''\n|Ship acquired=30 November 1953\n|Ship commissioned= 31 March 1969\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=yes\n|Ship renamed=''YAC-15'', 31 March 1965\n|Ship reclassified=Auxiliary stock craft (YAC), 31 March 1965\n|Ship identification=  Hull symbol: PF-296/YAC-15\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship fate=Returned to United States, 9 July 1971\n|Ship status=Unknown\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption={{sfn|Navsource}}\n|Ship class= {{sclass-|Tacoma|frigate|2}} [[patrol frigate]]\n|Ship displacement={{Tacoma class frigate displacement}}\n|Ship length= {{Tacoma class frigate length}}\n|Ship beam= {{Tacoma class frigate beam}}\n|Ship draft= {{Tacoma class frigate draft}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship power= {{Tacoma class frigate power}}\n|Ship propulsion={{Tacoma class frigate propulsion}}\n|Ship speed= {{Tacoma class frigate speed}}\n|Ship range= \n|Ship complement=190\n|Ship armament={{Tacoma class frigate armament}}\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''USS ''Albuquerque'' (PG-115/PF-7)''', a {{sclass-|Tacoma|frigate|0}} [[patrol frigate]] in commission from 1943 to 1945 and from 1950 to 1953, was the first ship of the [[United States Navy]] to be named for [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]. She also served in the [[Soviet Navy]] as '''''EK-14''''' and in the [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] as '''JDS ''Tochi'' (PF-16/PF-296)''' and as '''''YAC-15'''''.\n\n==Construction and commissioning==\n''Albuquerque'', originally classified as a patrol [[gunboat|patrol gunboat]], '''PG-115''', but reclassified as a patrol frigate, '''PF-7''', on 15 April 1943, was [[Keel laying|laid down]] under a [[Maritime Commission]] (MARCOM) contract, MC hull 1425, on 20 July 1943, at the [[Permanente Metals]] [[Richmond Shipyards|Richmond Shipyard #4]], [[Richmond, California|Richmond]], California. [[Ship naming and launching|Launched]] on 14 September 1943, sponsored by Mrs. B. L. Livingstone, the ship was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 20 December 1943, with [[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] Wayne L. Goff, [[USCG]], in command.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n==Service history==\n\n===U.S. Navy, World War II, 1943&ndash;1945===\nAfter [[Fitting-out|fitting out]] and [[Shakedown (testing)|shakedown]] training, ''Albuquerque'' stood out from [[Treasure Island, California|Treasure Island]], California, on 24 March 1944, bound for [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]], Washington. She arrived at Seattle, on 26 March 1944, and remained there until getting underway on 5 April 1944, as an escort for a [[convoy]] bound for the [[Territory of Alaska]]. She and her convoy arrived at [[Dutch Harbor, Alaska|Dutch Harbor]], on [[Unalaska Island]], in the [[Aleutian Islands]], on 16 April 1944, where she  was assigned to [[Escort Division 27]]. After the [[Liberty ship]] {{SS|John Straub||2}}, operating as a [[cargo ship]] for the [[United States Army]], either struck a [[naval mine|mine]] or was [[torpedo]]ed by the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] [[submarine]] {{ship|Japanese submarine|I-180||2}} and broke in two in the [[Pacific Ocean]] at {{coord|54|22|N|163|24|W|name=SS ''John Straub''}}, approximately {{convert|20|nmi}} southeast of [[Sanak Island]] in the [[Fox Islands (Alaska)|Fox Islands]] subgroup of the [[Aleutian Islands]] on 19 April 1944 and her [[Bow (ship)|bow]] section sank, ''Albuquerque'' [[Scuttling|scuttled]] her [[stern]] section.<ref name=alaskashipwrecksj>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-j/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (J)]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/LibShipsJo.html |title=Liberty Ships \u2013 Joaquin \u2013 Johns |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor the rest of 1944 and the first half of 1945, ''Albuquerque'' shepherded convoys between various Alaskan ports and conducted patrols around the Aleutian Islands and in the [[Bering Sea]].{{sfn|DANFS|2015}} Between 5 June and 14 July 1945, ''Albuquerque'' made a round-trip voyage from Dutch Harbor to Seattle and back. Selected for transfer to the [[Soviet Navy]] in [[Project Hula]] &ndash; a secret program for the transfer of U.S. Navy ships to the Soviet Navy at [[Cold Bay, Alaska|Cold Bay]], Alaska, in anticipation of the [[Soviet Union]] joining the [[Pacific War|war against Japan]] &ndash; she then proceeded to Cold Bay and began training her new Soviet crew.{{sfn|Russell|1997|p=39}}\n\n===Soviet Navy, 1945\u20131949===\n\nFollowing the completion of training for her Soviet crew, ''Albuquerque'' was [[Ship decommissioning|decommissioned]] on 16 August 1945, at Cold Bay, and transferred to the Soviet Union under [[Lend-Lease]] immediately along with her [[sister ship]]s {{USS|Tacoma|PF-3|3}}, {{USS|Sausalito|PF-4|3}}, {{USS|Hoquiam|PF-5|3}}, {{USS|Pasco|PF-6|3}}, and {{USS|Everett|PF-8|3}}. Commissioned into the Soviet Navy immediately,{{efn|name=fn1}}{{efn|name=fn3}} ''Albuquerque'' was designated as a ''storozhevoi korabl'' (\"escort ship\") and renamed '''''EK-14'''''{{efn|name=fn2}} in Soviet service. She soon departed Cold Bay, bound for [[Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky]] in the Soviet Union, where she served as a patrol vessel in the [[Soviet Far East]].{{sfn|Russell|1997|p=39}}\n\nIn February 1946, the United States began negotiations for the return of ships loaned to the Soviet Union for use during World War II. On 8 May 1947, [[United States Secretary of the Navy]] [[James V. Forrestal]] informed the [[United States Department of State]] that the [[United States Department of the Navy]] wanted 480 of the 585 combatant ships it had transferred to the Soviet Union for World War II use returned, ''EK-14'' among them. Negotiations for the return of the ships were protracted, but on 15 November 1949, the Soviet Union finally returned ''EK-14'' to the US Navy at [[United States Fleet Activities Yokosuka|Yokosuka]], [[Japan]].{{sfn|Russell|1997|pp=37\u201339}}\n\n===U.S. Navy, Korean War, 1950&ndash;1953===\nReverting to her former name, ''Albuquerque'' lay idle in the [[Pacific Reserve Fleet]] at Yokosuka until the outbreak of the [[Korean War]], on 25 June 1950, created a demand for more US Navy escort ships. Following repairs and refurbishment, she was recommissioned at Yokosuka, on 3 October 1950, with Lieutenant Commander Claude O. Lowe in command. For the next 10 months, she escorted convoys and conducted patrols between Yokosuka, [[Hong Kong]], and [[Singapore]]. In August 1951, she operated between Yokosuka and [[Subic Bay]] on [[Luzon]] in the [[Philippine Islands]]. On 10 December 1951, she departed Yokosuka, stopped at [[United States Fleet Activities Sasebo|Sasebo]], Japan, and, on 15 September 1951, got underway from Sasebo for patrol and escort duty along the eastern coast of [[Korea]].  As a unit of [[Escort Division 5]], [[Destroyer]] [[Flotilla]] 3, [[United States Pacific Fleet]], she spent the rest of September 1951 and most of October 1951 operating along the Korean coast.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n''Albuquerque'' concluded that duty on 26 October 1951, when she departed Sasebo bound for Hong Kong. She arrived in at Hong Kong on 30 October 1951 and remained there, presumably in some sort of [[station ship]] status, until March 1952. On 6 March 1952, she stood out of Hong Kong, bound for Subic Bay in the Philippines. From Subic Bay, she headed back to Japan, returning to Sasebo on 16 May 1952. Based there, she resumed [[patrol]] and escort duties along the eastern coast of Korea. That assignment lasted for about six weeks. In July 1952, she again visited Subic Bay, and on 26 July 1952, arrived in Hong Kong. She once more made an extended visit to Hong Kong, until finally departing in mid-November 1952. After a visit to Subic Bay, she returned to Sasebo, on 3 December 1952, and resumed duty along the eastern coast of Korea. On 28 February 1953, she was decommissioned at Yokosuka.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n===Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force, 1953&ndash;1968===\n\n{{other ships|Japanese ship Tochi}}\n\nOn 30 November 1953, the United States loaned the ship to Japan, and she was commissioned in the [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] as {{Nihongo|'''JDS ''Tochi'' (PF-16)'''|\u3068\u3061 (PF-16)||\"[[aesculus turbinata]]\"}}.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} The JMSDF reclassified her as '''''PF-296''''' on 1 September 1957.{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} The US Navy struck her from the [[Navy List]] on 1 December 1961, but she was returned briefly to US Navy custody on 28 August 1962, before the United States almost simultaneously transferred her back to Japan permanently. Reclassified as an \"auxiliary stock craft\" (YAC) and renamed '''''YAC-15''''' on 31 March 1965,{{Sfn|The Naval Database}} she was decommissioned on 31 March 1969, and returned to US custody on 9 July 1971, for disposal. Her final disposition is unknown.{{sfn|Navsource}}\n\n==Awards==\n\nThe US Navy awarded ''Albuquerque'' three [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle stars]] for her Korean War service.{{sfn|DANFS|2015}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|refs=\n{{efn|name=fn1|The [http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/a5/albuquerque-i.htm ''Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships'' ''Albuquerque'' I\"] article states that ''Albuquerque'' was transferred to the Soviet Navy on 17 August 1945, and [http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/08007.htm NavSource Online: Frigate Photo Archive Albuquerque (PF 7) ex-PG-115] and [http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/pf7.htm hazegray.org ''Albuquerque''] repeat this date, but more recent research in Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, p. 39, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], reports that the transfer date was 16 August 1945. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n{{efn|name=fn2|[http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/08007.htm NavSource Online: Frigate Photo Archive Albuquerque (PF 7) ex-PG-115] asserts that ''Albuquerque'' was named ''EK-16'' in Soviet Navy service without citing a source for this name, but Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, p. 39, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], reports that the ship's Soviet name was ''EK-14''. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n{{efn|name=fn3|According to Russell, Richard A., ''Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan'', Washington, D.C.: [[Naval Historical Center]], 1997, {{ISBN|0-945274-35-1}}, which includes access to Soviet-era records unavailable during the [[Cold War]], Project Hula ships were commissioned into the Soviet Navy simultaneously with their transfer from the U.S. Navy; see photo captions on p. 24 regarding the transfers of various [[large infantry landing craft]] (LCI(L)s) and information on p. 27 about the transfer of {{USS|Coronado|PF-38}}, which Russell says typified the transfer process. As sources, Russell cites Department of the Navy, ''Ships Data: U.S. Naval Vessels'' Volume II, 1 January 1949, (NAVSHIPS 250-012), Washington, DC: Bureau of Ships, 1949; and Berezhnoi, S. S., ''Flot SSSR: Korabli i suda lendliza: Spravochnik'' (\"The Soviet Navy: Lend-Lease Ships and Vessels: A Reference\"), St. Petersburg, Russia: Belen, 1994.}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite DANFS \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | url = https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/nhhc/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/a/albuquerque-i.html \n  | title = Albuquerque I (PF-7)\n  | publisher = Naval History and Heritage Command \n  | date = 15 June 2015\n  | accessdate = 9 November 2018\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|DANFS|2015}}\n  }}{{PD-notice}}\n* {{cite web\n  | url = http://shipbuildinghistory.com/shipyards/emergencylarge/krichmond.htm\n  | title = Kaiser Permanente No. 4, Richmond CA\n  | publisher =  www.ShipbuildingHistory.com\n  | date = 5 February 2014\n  | accessdate = 9 November 2018\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Kaiser No. 4|2014}}\n  }}\n* {{cite web \n  | url = http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/08007.htm \n  | title= Albuquerque (PF 7)\n  | publisher= Navsource.org \n  | date= \n  | accessdate= 9 November 2018\n  | ref= {{sfnRef|Navsource}}\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  |last= Russell\n  |first= Richard A.\n  |title= Project Hula: Secret Soviet-American Cooperation in the War Against Japan\n  |location= Washington, D.C.\n  |publisher= [[Naval Historical Center]]\n  |date= 1997\n  |ref= harv\n  |isbn= 0-945274-35-1\n  }}\n* {{cite web\n  | title = The Naval Database: JMSDF Kusu class patrol frigate (PF296) Tochi \n  | url = http://hush.gooside.com/name/t/To/tochi.html#anchor7543 \n  | language=Japanese \n  | ref = {{SfnRef|The Naval Database}} \n  | accessdate = 2014-09-22 \n  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{navsource|12/08007|USS Albuquerque}}\n* [http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/pf7.htm hazegray.org: USS ''Albuquerque'']\n\n <!-- non-breaking space to keep AWB drones from altering the space before the navbox-->\n\n{{Tacoma class frigate|others}}\n{{Kaiser, Richmond Ship Yards}}\n{{Project Hula ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albuquerque (PF-7)}}\n[[Category:Tacoma-class frigates]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Richmond, California]]\n[[Category:1943 ships]]\n[[Category:World War II frigates and destroyer escorts of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Navy New Mexico-related ships]]\n[[Category:Tacoma-class frigates of the Soviet Navy]]\n[[Category:World War II frigates of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Cold War frigates of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Cold War frigates and destroyer escorts of the United States]]\n[[Category:Korean War frigates and destroyer escorts of the United States]]\n[[Category:Tacoma-class frigates of the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]]\n[[Category:Ships transferred under Project Hula]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "co